'''Montero Lamar Hill''' (born April 9, 1999), better known by his stage name<!-- please do not add "professionally known" as most people know him by this name only--> '''Lil Nas X''' ({{IPAc-en|n|ɑː|z}} {{Respell|NAHZ}}), is an American rapper, singer, and songwriter. He rose to prominence with the release of his 2019 [[country rap]] single "[[Old Town Road]]," the longest-running number-one song (at [[List of Billboard Hot 100 chart achievements and milestones|19 weeks]]) since the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]'s 1958 inception.<ref name="autogenerated2">{{Cite web |date=August 13, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X hit ''Old Town Road'' makes Billboard charts history |url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-billboard-charts-history |access-date=August 29, 2019 |publisher=[[Fox News]] |language=en-US |agency=Associated Press |archive-date=August 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829000933/https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-billboard-charts-history |url-status=live }}</ref> Simultaneously, he [[came out]] as [[homosexuality|gay]], the only artist to do so while having a number-one record.<ref name="VultureHistory">{{Cite web |last=Thompson |first=Paul |date=July 17, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Is Strategically Closing in on History |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/07/how-lil-nas-x-could-make-billboard-chart-history.html |access-date=July 17, 2019 |website=Vulture |archive-date=July 18, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718070502/https://www.vulture.com/2019/07/how-lil-nas-x-could-make-billboard-chart-history.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Following the success of "Old Town Road", Lil Nas X signed with [[Columbia Records]] to release his debut [[extended play]] (EP) ''[[7 (Lil Nas X EP)|7]]'' (2019), which spawned two follow-up singles⁠: "[[Panini (song)|Panini]]" and "[[Rodeo (Lil Nas X and Cardi B song)|Rodeo]]" (featuring [[Cardi B]] or [[Nas]]); the former peaked at number five on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, while the latter peaked at number 22. His debut studio album, ''[[Montero (album)|Montero]]'' (2021), peaked at number two on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and earned a nomination for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] at the [[64th Annual Grammy Awards]]. It was supported by the ''Billboard'' Hot 100-number one singles "[[Montero (Call Me by Your Name)]]" and "[[Industry Baby]]" (featuring [[Jack Harlow]]), along with the top-ten single "[[Thats What I Want]]".

Known for his queer visuals and social media presence,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wheeler |first=André |title=Lil Nas X: 'I 100% want to represent the LGBT community' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/04/lil-nas-x-i-100-want-to-represent-the-lgbt-community |access-date=May 27, 2023 |website=The Guardian |date=April 4, 2020 |language=en |archive-date=November 25, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221125205024/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/04/lil-nas-x-i-100-want-to-represent-the-lgbt-community |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Raza-Sheikh |first=Zoya |title=How Lil Nas X became a revolutionary queer artist for a generation |url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/how-lil-nas-x-became-a-revolutionary-queer-artist-for-a-generation/ |access-date=May 27, 2023 |website=GayTimes |date=April 2021 |language=en |archive-date=May 27, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230527224331/https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/how-lil-nas-x-became-a-revolutionary-queer-artist-for-a-generation/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Lil Nas X has received [[List of awards and nominations received by Lil Nas X|numerous accolades]], including two [[Grammy Award]]s, five [[Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], five [[MTV Video Music Awards]], two [[BET Hip Hop Awards]], two [[iHeartRadio Music Awards]] and two [[American Music Awards]]. "Old Town Road" ranks as the [[List of best-selling singles in the United States|second highest-certified song in the United States]]—with 17 platinum certifications.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Andriyashchuk |first1=Yuriy |title=Post Malone and Swae Lee's "Sunflower" becomes highest certified single in US RIAA history, at 18× platinum |url=https://hip-hopvibe.com/news/post-malone-and-swae-lees-sunflower-becomes-highest-certified-single-in-us-riaa-history-at-18x-platinum/ |website=Hip-Hop Vibe |date=May 31, 2023 |access-date=July 3, 2023 |archive-date=July 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230703011251/https://hip-hopvibe.com/news/post-malone-and-swae-lees-sunflower-becomes-highest-certified-single-in-us-riaa-history-at-18x-platinum/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He was placed on ''[[Forbes]]''{{'}} [[30 Under 30]] in 2020, and ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' named him one of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]] the following year.<ref name="auto">{{Cite web |last=Greenburg |first=Zack O'Malley |title=Lil Nas X, Normani, Maluma And The 30 Under 30 Music Class Of 2020 |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2019/12/03/lil-nas-x-normani-maluma-and-the-30-under-30-music-class-of-2020/ |access-date=April 5, 2020 |website=Forbes |language=en |archive-date=December 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203134804/https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2019/12/03/lil-nas-x-normani-maluma-and-the-30-under-30-music-class-of-2020/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He became the youngest honoree in the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]] in 2022 upon receiving the [[Hal David Starlight Award]] in May of that year.<ref name="Sachdeva">{{Cite web |last=Sachdeva |first=Maanya |date=September 16, 2021 |title=Britney Spears, Scarlett Johansson and Jason Sudeikis among Time 100 most influential |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/time-100-most-influential-celebrities-b1921324.html |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220614/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/time-100-most-influential-celebrities-b1921324.html |archive-date=June 14, 2022 |access-date=November 13, 2021 |website=[[The Independent]] |language=en}}</ref>

==Early life and education==
Montero Lamar Hill was born in [[Lithia Springs, Georgia]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Najja Parker |title="I'm not angry": Lil Nas X addresses those who bullied him for coming out |language=en |work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/world/not-angry-lil-nas-addresses-those-who-bullied-him-for-coming-out/vrAfj2Xezbv0fBek76Zx7J/ |access-date=July 9, 2019 |archive-date=July 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709095225/https://www.ajc.com/news/world/not-angry-lil-nas-addresses-those-who-bullied-him-for-coming-out/vrAfj2Xezbv0fBek76Zx7J/ |url-status=live }}</ref> on April 9, 1999.<ref name="Chow">{{Cite magazine |last=Chow |first=Andrew R. |date=March 30, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X on 'Old Town Road' and the Billboard Controversy |url=https://time.com/5561466/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-billboard/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913012423/https://time.com/5561466/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-billboard/ |archive-date=September 13, 2019 |access-date=December 2, 2023 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |language=en}}</ref> He was named after the [[Mitsubishi Montero]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rice |first=Nicholas |title=Lil Nas X Details Where His Birth Name Came From — and the Origin of His Stage Moniker |url=https://people.com/music/lil-nas-x-origin-of-birth-name-stage-moniker/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112222422/https://people.com/music/lil-nas-x-origin-of-birth-name-stage-moniker/?amp=true |archive-date=January 12, 2021 |access-date=December 2, 2023 |website=[[Peoplemag]] |language=en}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was six,<ref name=":8">{{Cite magazine |last=Chow |first=Andrew R. |date=August 15, 2019 |title='It Feels Like I'm Chosen to Do This.' Inside the Record-Breaking Rise of Lil Nas X |url=https://time.com/5652803/lil-nas-x/ |magazine=Time |language=en |access-date=August 19, 2019 |archive-date=August 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815120635/https://time.com/5652803/lil-nas-x/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and he settled in the [[Bankhead Courts]] [[housing project]] in the [[Bankhead, Atlanta|Bankhead]] neighborhood of [[Atlanta]] with his mother and grandmother. Three years later, he moved in with his father, a gospel singer,<ref name=":8" /> north of the city in [[Austell]]. Although initially reluctant to leave, he later regarded it as an important decision, "There's so much shit going on in Atlanta—if I would have stayed there, I would have fallen in with the wrong crowd."<ref name="rs" /> He started "using the Internet heavily right around the time when [[meme]]s started to become their own form of entertainment"; about when he was 13.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Carmichael |first=Rodney |date=April 10, 2019 |title=Wrangler On His Booty: Lil Nas X On The Making And The Magic Of 'Old Town Road' |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/04/10/711167412/wrangler-on-his-booty-lil-nas-x-on-the-making-and-the-magic-of-old-town-road |access-date=August 20, 2019 |publisher=NPR |language=en |archive-date=August 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820221624/https://www.npr.org/2019/04/10/711167412/wrangler-on-his-booty-lil-nas-x-on-the-making-and-the-magic-of-old-town-road |url-status=live }}</ref>

He spent much of his teenage years alone, and turned to creating memes on the internet.<ref name=":8" /> His teenage years also saw him struggling with his [[coming out]] to himself as being gay; he prayed that it was just a phase,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Towle |first=Andy |date=September 30, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Says He Prayed as a Teen That His Gay Inclinations Were Just a Phase: WATCH |url=https://www.towleroad.com/2019/09/lil-nas-x-gay-phase/ |access-date=October 1, 2019 |website=[[Towleroad News]] |language=en-US |archive-date=October 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001142240/https://www.towleroad.com/2019/09/lil-nas-x-gay-phase/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=King |first=Gayle |date=September 30, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X opens up about the difficulties of coming out: "We still have a long way to go" |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/lil-nas-x-interview-gayle-king-the-difficulties-of-coming-out-we-still-have-a-long-way-to-go-today-2019-09-30/ |access-date=October 8, 2019 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |language=en |archive-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004125458/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/lil-nas-x-interview-gayle-king-the-difficulties-of-coming-out-we-still-have-a-long-way-to-go-today-2019-09-30/ |url-status=live }}</ref> but around 16 or 17 he came to accept it.<ref>{{Cite web |last=King |first=Gayle |date=October 1, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X on the origins of 'Old Town Road': "The line just comes to me" |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-lyrics-origins-the-line-just-comes-to-me/ |access-date=October 8, 2019 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |archive-date=October 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002004448/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-lyrics-origins-the-line-just-comes-to-me/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He began playing trumpet in the fourth grade and was first chair by his junior high years, but quit out of fear of looking uncool.<ref name="YouTube 2019">{{Cite web |date=November 20, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Goes Undercover on Reddit, Twitter and Instagram |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V_JjNnGUOfE |access-date=November 21, 2019 |website=GQ |archive-date=November 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122123321/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V_JjNnGUOfE |url-status=live }}</ref>

Hill attended [[Lithia Springs High School]], from which he graduated in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Daniel |first=Ron |date=April 11, 2019 |title=Lithia grad Lil Nas X has top song in America |url=https://douglascountysentinel.com/news/1887/lithia-grad-lil-nas-x-has-top-song-in-america/ |url-access=subscription |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626183008/https://douglascountysentinel.com/news/1887/lithia-grad-lil-nas-x-has-top-song-in-america/ |archive-date=June 26, 2019 |access-date=April 22, 2019 |website=Douglas County Sentinel}}</ref> He then enrolled at the [[University of West Georgia]], where he [[majored]] in [[computer science]], but later dropped out after one year to pursue a music career.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wheeler |first=Andre |date=April 4, 2020 |title=Lil Nas X: 'I 100% want to represent the LGBT community' |language=en |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/04/lil-nas-x-i-100-want-to-represent-the-lgbt-community |access-date=January 27, 2022 |archive-date=November 25, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221125205024/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/04/lil-nas-x-i-100-want-to-represent-the-lgbt-community |url-status=live }}</ref> During this time, he stayed with his sister and supported himself with jobs at [[Zaxby's]] restaurants and the [[Six Flags Over Georgia]] theme park.<ref name="rs">{{Cite magazine |last=Eels |first=Josh |date=May 20, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X: Inside the Rise of a Hip-Hop Cowboy |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-interview-new-album-836393/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=May 20, 2019 |archive-date=July 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702014754/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-interview-new-album-836393/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2019, he revisited his high school to perform a surprise concert.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Naumann |first=Ryan |date=September 10, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Drops By His Old High School To Give Surprise Concert |work=The Blast |url=https://theblast.com/c/lil-nas-x-surprise-high-school-visit-concert-students-children-hospital |access-date=September 11, 2019 |archive-date=September 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926183632/https://theblast.com/c/lil-nas-x-surprise-high-school-visit-concert-students-children-hospital |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Career ==
===2015–2017: Internet personality and ''Nasarati''===
Hill said he began to isolate himself from "outside-of-class activities" during his teenage years. He spent large amounts of time online in hopes of building a following as an [[internet personality]] to promote his work, but he was unsure what to focus on creatively. In a ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' interview he stated, "I was doing Facebook comedy videos, then I moved over to Instagram, and then I hopped on Twitter ... where I really was a master. That was the first place where I could go viral."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Nilles |first=Billy |date=August 2, 2019 |title=Why Lil Nas X Breaking Records Is Such a Big Deal |url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1060868/why-lil-nas-x-breaking-billboard-records-is-such-a-big-deal |access-date=August 3, 2019 |publisher=E! |archive-date=August 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803061812/https://www.eonline.com/news/1060868/why-lil-nas-x-breaking-billboard-records-is-such-a-big-deal |url-status=live }}</ref> He also posted short-format comedy videos on Facebook and [[Vine (service)|Vine]].<ref name="rs" />

During this period, he reportedly created and ran [[Nicki Minaj]] fan accounts on Twitter, including one called "@NasMaraj", according to a [[New York (magazine)|''New York'' Magazine]] investigation.<ref name="NYMag">{{Cite web |last=Feldman |first=Brian |date=April 5, 2019 |title=Before 'Old Town Road,' Lil Nas X Was a Tweetdecker |url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/04/lil-nas-x-was-a-popular-twitter-user-before-old-town-road.html |access-date=April 5, 2019 |website=New York |archive-date=July 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706055802/http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/04/lil-nas-x-was-a-popular-twitter-user-before-old-town-road.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Reinstein |first=Julia |date=April 5, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Used To Be A Tweetdecker |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/juliareinstein/lil-nas-x-tweetdecker-old-town-road |access-date=September 3, 2019 |website=BuzzFeed News |archive-date=September 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903195758/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/juliareinstein/lil-nas-x-tweetdecker-old-town-road |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2017, this account gained attention for its [[flash fiction]]-style interactive "scenario threads" popularized on Twitter using dashboard app [[TweetDeck]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=N/A |first=Mix |date=July 10, 2017 |title=One cryptic storyteller is using Twitter to craft thrilling interactive fiction |url=https://thenextweb.com/twitter/2017/07/10/twitter-storyteller-interactive-fiction/ |access-date=April 3, 2019 |website=The Next Web |archive-date=April 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403092223/https://thenextweb.com/twitter/2017/07/10/twitter-storyteller-interactive-fiction/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hill |first=Montero |date=August 4, 2017 |title=nasmaraj (u/nasmaraj) |url=https://www.reddit.com/user/nasmaraj |access-date=April 3, 2019 |via=Reddit |archive-date=April 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403173715/https://www.reddit.com/user/nasmaraj |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="NYMag" /> The investigation linked @NasMaraj to the practice of "Tweetdecking", or using multiple accounts in collaboration to artificially make certain tweets go viral. The @NasMaraj account was suspended by Twitter due to "violating spam policies".<ref name="NYMag" /> After the suspension of @NasMaraj, ''New York'' Magazine's investigation concluded that he subsequently opened a new account with handle "@NasMarai", and that his current Twitter account at the time was a repurposed version of that "@NasMarai" account with a changed handle.<ref name="NYMag" /> After media reports linked Lil Nas X to the Minaj fan accounts, he called the reports a "misunderstanding", effectively denying having run the accounts.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Carmichael |first=Rodney |date=April 10, 2019 |title=Wrangler On His Booty: Lil Nas X On The Making And The Magic Of 'Old Town Road' |publisher=NPR |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/04/10/711167412/wrangler-on-his-booty-lil-nas-x-on-the-making-and-the-magic-of-old-town-road |access-date=April 29, 2019 |archive-date=April 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428172435/https://www.npr.org/2019/04/10/711167412/wrangler-on-his-booty-lil-nas-x-on-the-making-and-the-magic-of-old-town-road |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Lil Nas X on His Connection to Nicki Minaj Stan Account: 'It's Like a Big Misunderstanding' |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/04/lil-nas-x-distances-himself-from-nicki-minaj-stan-account |access-date=April 29, 2019 |website=Complex |archive-date=May 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502065425/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/04/lil-nas-x-distances-himself-from-nicki-minaj-stan-account |url-status=live }}</ref> However, in May 2020, Lil Nas X admitted, in a tweet, to being a fan of Minaj. He explained why he initially denied it, stating that if people knew he was a fan of hers, they would think he was gay: "People will assume if you had an entire fan page dedicated to nicki u are gay. and the rap/music industry ain't exactly built or accepting of gay men yet". On June 17, 2020, Minaj responded to Nas, tweeting "It was a bit of a sting when you denied being a barb, but I understand. Congratulations on building up your confidence to speak your truth". Lil Nas apologized to Minaj, saying he "felt so bad, hoping u wouldn't see my denial".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Curto |first=Justin |date=June 10, 2020 |title=Nicki Minaj Congratulates Lil Nas X on Coming Out As a Barb |url=https://www.vulture.com/amp/2020/06/nicki-minaj-lil-nas-x-stan-tweets.html |access-date=July 11, 2020 |website=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]] |archive-date=June 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200625093825/https://www.vulture.com/amp/2020/06/nicki-minaj-lil-nas-x-stan-tweets.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The @NasMarai account was later mentioned in a ''[[New York Times Magazine]]'' article, which described Hill as having spent "every waking hour online, tweeting as @nasmaraj".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hughes |first=Jazmine |date=July 7, 2021 |title=The Subversive Joy of Lil Nas X's Gay Pop Stardom |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/07/07/magazine/lil-nas-x.html |access-date=July 29, 2021 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=July 29, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210729073212/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/07/07/magazine/lil-nas-x.html |url-status=live }}</ref> It is also referenced in the music video for "Sun Goes Down", which shows Lil Nas X's many struggles growing up as a closeted teen and embracing his sexuality; he is seen tweeting while in high school from an account named "nasmiraj" as the lyrics "I'd be by the phone, stanning Nicki morning into dawn" play.<ref>{{Citation |title=Lil Nas X – SUN GOES DOWN (Official Video) | date=May 20, 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U3BVFY9wnTw |access-date=July 29, 2021 |language=en |archive-date=July 29, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210729025248/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U3BVFY9wnTw |url-status=live }}</ref>

Sometime in the year 2018, Hill landed on music as a path to success, and started writing and recording songs in his closet.<ref name=":8" /> He adopted the name Lil Nas X, which is a tribute to the rapper [[Nas]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Prahl |first=Amanda |date=July 2, 2019 |title=His Name Pays Tribute to a Famous Rapper |url=https://www.popsugar.co.uk/celebrity/photo-gallery/46339586/embed/46339575 |access-date=November 1, 2019 |website=[[PopSugar]] |publisher=[[Group Nine Media]]}}</ref> On July 24, 2018, Lil Nas released his first mixtape ''Nasarati'' on [[SoundCloud]], though it was not received with immediate fame; ''Nasarati'' would be removed from streaming services soon after the release of ''Old Town Road'' due to a copyright conflict and therefore would never gain significant traction.<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 25, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Is Reportedly Being Sued Over A Song From His First Mixtape |url=https://uproxx.com/music/lil-nas-x-sued-carry-on-nasarati/ |access-date=January 20, 2022 |website=UPROXX |language=en-US |archive-date=January 20, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120221936/https://uproxx.com/music/lil-nas-x-sued-carry-on-nasarati/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In late October 2018, he happened to hear the beat that would become "[[Old Town Road]]".<ref name=":8" />

=== 2018–2019: Breakthrough with "Old Town Road" and ''7'' ===
{{Main|Old Town Road}}
[[File:Lil Nas X (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Lil Nas X in April 2019]]
On December 3, 2018, Lil Nas X released the [[country rap]] song "[[Old Town Road]]".{{efn|"Old Town Road" has been variously described by publications as a [[country rap]],<ref name="Leight">{{Cite magazine |last=Leight |first=Elias |date=April 9, 2019 |title='Old Town Road' by Lil Nas X Is Officially the Number One Song in America |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-number-one-hot-100-816584/ |url-status=live |magazine=Rolling Stone |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409184239/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-number-one-hot-100-816584/ |archive-date=April 9, 2019 |access-date=April 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name="Ivie">{{Cite web |last=Ivie |first=Devon |date=April 6, 2019 |title=''Billboard'' Defends Lil Nas X's 'Old Town Road' Removal from the Country Charts |url=https://www.vulture.com/amp/2019/04/billboard-defends-lil-nas-xs-old-town-road-country-removal.html |access-date=April 11, 2019 |website=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]] |archive-date=April 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406194401/https://www.vulture.com/amp/2019/04/billboard-defends-lil-nas-xs-old |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Caramanica |first=Jon |date=April 11, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X's Smash Makes Country Wonder If Rap Is Friend or Foe. Again. |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/11/arts/music/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-country-rap.html |url-status=live |access-date=May 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412020521/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/11/arts/music/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-country-rap.html |archive-date=April 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Ashrawi |first=Sama'an |title=Before 'Old Town Road': The Evolution of Country Rap Tunes |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/04/evolution-of-country-rap-songs/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412181834/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/04/evolution-of-country-rap-songs/ |archive-date=April 12, 2019 |access-date=May 28, 2019 |website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]}}</ref> [[country music|country]],<ref name="Manns">{{Cite web |last=Manns |first=Keydra |title=Was ''Billboard'' Wrong to Pull 'Old Town Road' from the Country Chart? |url=https://www.nj.com/tylt/2019/03/was-billboard-wrong-to-pull-old-town-road-from-the-country-chart.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331003553/https://www.nj.com/tylt/2019/03/was-billboard-wrong-to-pull-old-town-road-from-the-country-chart.html |archive-date=March 31, 2019 |access-date=April 11, 2019 |website=[[New Jersey On-Line]] |publisher=[[Advance Local]]}}</ref><ref name="Richards">{{Cite news |last=Richards |first=Chris |title='Old Town Road' Is a Smash. Will It Mutate into 'Baby Shark'? |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/old-town-road-is-a-smash-will-it-mutate-into-baby-shark/2019/04/10/f8c4e498-5b01-11e9-842d-7d3ed7eb3957_story.html |url-status=live |access-date=May 4, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411020346/https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/old-town-road-is-a-smash-will-it-mutate-into-baby-shark/2019/04/10/f8c4e498-5b01-11e9-842d-7d3ed7eb3957_story.html |archive-date=April 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Zemler |first=Emily |date=May 7, 2019 |title=Watch Lil Nas X Perform 'Old Town Road' on ''Desus and Mero'' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/watch-lil-nas-x-perform-old-town-town-desus-mero-832280/ |url-status=live |magazine=Rolling Stone |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507094454/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/watch-lil-nas-x-perform-old-town-town-desus-mero-832280/ |archive-date=May 7, 2019 |access-date=May 28, 2019}}</ref> [[trap music|trap]],<ref name="Gillespie">{{Cite web |last=Gillespie |first=Katherine |title=This Billy Ray Cyrus Remix of 'Old Town Road' Slaps |url=http://www.papermag.com/old-town-road-billy-ray-cyrus-2633780650.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406133522/http://www.papermag.com/old-town-road-billy-ray-cyrus-2633780650.html |archive-date=April 6, 2019 |access-date=April 11, 2019 |website=[[PAPER Magazine]]}}</ref><ref name="Spanos">{{Cite magazine |last=Spanos |first=Brittany |author-link=Brittany Spanos |date=April 5, 2019 |title=Song You Need to Know: Lil Nas X and Billy Ray Cyrus, 'Old Town Road (Remix)' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/old-town-road-remix-lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-816658/ |url-status=live |magazine=Rolling Stone |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405211915/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/old-town-road-remix-lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-816658/ |archive-date=April 5, 2019 |access-date=April 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Butler |first=Bethonie |title=''Billboard'' Tried to Fit 'Old Town Road' into a Neat Box. But That's Not How We Listen to Music Anyway. |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/04/13/billboard-tried-fit-old-town-road-into-neat-box-thats-not-how-we-listen-music-anyway/ |url-status=live |access-date=May 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509221658/https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/04/13/billboard-tried-fit-old-town-road-into-neat-box-thats-not-how-we-listen-music-anyway/ |archive-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref> or [[Southern hip hop]] song.<ref name="Luckerson">{{Cite web |last=Luckerson |first=Victor |title=Lil Nas X and the Costume of Country Rap |url=https://www.theringer.com/music/2019/4/10/18302094/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-billy-ray-cyrus-southern-rap-country-trap-hick-hop |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410142401/https://www.theringer.com/music/2019/4/10/18302094/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-billy-ray-cyrus-southern-rap-country-trap-hick-hop |archive-date=April 10, 2019 |access-date=April 11, 2019 |website=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]}}</ref> Lil Nas X stated that he regards it as a "[[country trap]]" song.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Yoo |first=Noah |date=March 27, 2019 |title=Billboard Removes Lil Nas X's Viral Song 'Old Town Road' from Country Chart |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/lil-nas-x-viral-hit-old-town-road-removed-from-billboard-hot-country-songs-chart/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331144550/https://pitchfork.com/news/lil-nas-x-viral-hit-old-town-road-removed-from-billboard-hot-country-songs-chart/ |archive-date=March 31, 2019 |access-date=May 28, 2019 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]}}</ref>}} He bought the [[Hip hop production|beat]] for the song anonymously on beat-selling platform [[BeatStars]] from [[Dutch people|Dutch]] producer [[YoungKio]] for $30;<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ifeanyi |first=K. C. |date=May 7, 2019 |title=How a kid from the Netherlands and a startup called BeatStars led to Old Town Road |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90344161/how-a-kid-from-the-netherlands-and-a-startup-called-beatstars-led-to-old-town-road |access-date=June 23, 2022 |website=Fast Company |language=en-US |archive-date=July 5, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220705214212/https://www.fastcompany.com/90344161/how-a-kid-from-the-netherlands-and-a-startup-called-beatstars-led-to-old-town-road |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="BI">{{Cite web |last=Pamela Engel |date=May 31, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X's country-trap hit 'Old Town Road' samples a Nine Inch Nails song — and the band might have a claim to some of the royalties |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-nine-inch-nails-sample-2019-5 |access-date=June 24, 2019 |website=[[Business Insider]] |archive-date=June 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190625023032/https://www.businessinsider.com/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-nine-inch-nails-sample-2019-5 |url-status=live }}</ref> it samples [[Nine Inch Nails]]' track "34 Ghosts IV" from their sixth studio album ''[[Ghosts I–IV]]'' (2008).<ref name="RecordDeal">{{Cite magazine |last=Cirisano |first=Tatiana |date=March 22, 2019 |title='Old Town Road' Rapper Lil Nas X Signs to Columbia Records |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8502868/lil-nas-x-signs-columbia-records |magazine=Billboard |access-date=March 29, 2019 |archive-date=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831172217/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8502868/lil-nas-x-signs-columbia-records |url-status=live }}</ref> He recorded at a "humble" Atlanta studio, CinCoYo, on their "$20 Tuesdays", taking less than an hour.<ref>{{Cite web |last=King |first=Gayle |date=September 30, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X takes Gayle King inside the studio where he recorded 'Old Town Road' |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/lil-nas-x-inside-the-recording-studio-where-rapper-made-old-town-road/ |access-date=October 8, 2019 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |language=en |archive-date=October 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002160023/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/lil-nas-x-inside-the-recording-studio-where-rapper-made-old-town-road/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Lil Nas X began creating memes to promote "Old Town Road" before it was picked up by [[TikTok]] users.<ref name="Chow" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Lil Nas X TikTok Stats and Analytics Summary Profile |url=https://insiflow.com/tiktok/user/lilnasx |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210602220128/https://insiflow.com/tiktok/user/lilnasx |archive-date=June 2, 2021 |access-date=June 2, 2021 |website=Social Media Marketing & Management Dashboard |language=en}}</ref> TikTok encourages its 500 million global users to "endless imitation", with videos generating copies usually using the same music; the "app's frantic churn of content [...] acts as a potent incubator for viral music hits."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Zhang |first=Cat |date=November 13, 2019 |title=The Anatomy of a TikTok Hit |url=https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/the-anatomy-of-a-tiktok-hit/ |access-date=November 16, 2019 |website=[[Pitchfork (magazine)|Pitchfork]] |language=en |archive-date=November 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116135002/https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/the-anatomy-of-a-tiktok-hit/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Lil Nas X estimated he made about 100 [[Internet meme|memes]] to promote the song;<ref name=":8" /> it went viral in early 2019 due to the #Yeehaw Challenge meme on TikTok. Millions of users posted videos of themselves dressed as a [[Wrangler (profession)|wrangler]] or cowgirl, with most #yeehaw videos using the song for their soundtrack. As of July 2019, these videos have been viewed more than 67 million times.<ref name="Chow" /> Another core audience tied to social media is children who are hidden in the statistics of adult listeners.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Kopf |first=Dan |date=July 29, 2019 |title=One secret to Old Town Road's record-breaking success? Kids are obsessed with it |url=https://qz.com/quartzy/1675326/kids-are-obsessed-with-the-record-breaking-old-town-road/ |access-date=August 5, 2019 |website=Quartzy |language=en |archive-date=August 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805065800/https://qz.com/quartzy/1675326/kids-are-obsessed-with-the-record-breaking-old-town-road/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Quartz.com says the song certainly owes part of its success to the demographic, and notes they are attracted to the song being repetitive, easy to sing along to, and using lyrics about riding horses and tractors, which children can relate to.<ref name=":0" /> The track debuted at number 83 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart, later climbing to number one.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Kellner |first=Xander |date=March 13, 2019 |title=Spurred by a TikTok Meme, Lil Nas X Scores First Billboard Hot 100 Hit With 'Old Town Road' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8502208/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-no-83-hot-100 |magazine=Billboard |access-date=March 21, 2019 |archive-date=July 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713200109/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8502208/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-no-83-hot-100 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=April 8, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X's "Old Town Road" Leaps to No. 1 on the Hot 100 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8506256/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-number-one-hot-100 |magazine=Billboard |access-date=April 9, 2019 |archive-date=March 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307065823/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8506256/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-number-one-hot-100 |url-status=live }}</ref> It also debuted on the [[Hot Country Songs]] chart at number 19 and [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] at number 36.<ref name=":"4"">{{Cite magazine |last=Cirisano |first=Tatiana |date=March 14, 2019 |title=Labels Sparring Over Rapper Lil Nas X As 'Old Town Road' Rakes In Streams: Exclusive |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8502318/lil-nas-x-labels-bidding-old-town-road-exclusive |magazine=Billboard |access-date=March 21, 2019 |archive-date=June 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626183016/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8502318/lil-nas-x-labels-bidding-old-town-road-exclusive |url-status=live }}</ref> After an "intense bidding war", Lil Nas X signed with [[Columbia Records]] in March 2019.<ref name="Chow" /> ''Billboard'' controversially removed the song from the Hot Country songs chart in March 2019, telling ''[[Rolling Stone]]'':

{{Blockquote|text=When determining genres, a few factors are examined, but first and foremost is a musical composition. While "Old Town Road" incorporates references to country and cowboy imagery, it does not embrace enough elements of today's country music to chart in its current version.<ref name="Nast">{{Cite web |date=March 27, 2019 |title=Billboard Removes Lil Nas X's Viral Song "Old Town Road" from Country Chart |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/lil-nas-x-viral-hit-old-town-road-removed-from-billboard-hot-country-songs-chart/ |access-date=2019-04-08 |website=Pitchfork |archive-date=March 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331144550/https://pitchfork.com/news/lil-nas-x-viral-hit-old-town-road-removed-from-billboard-hot-country-songs-chart/ |url-status=live }}</ref>}}

[[File:Lil Nas X back stage at the MTV Video Music Awards 2019 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Lil Nas X at the [[2019 MTV Video Music Awards]]]]
In [[Robert Christgau]]'s opinion, "Taking 'Old Town Road' off the country chart strikes me as racist pure and simple, because [[country radio]] remains racist regardless of the [[Darius Rucker]]s and [[Kane Brown]]s it makes room for."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Christgau |first=Robert |author-link=Robert Christgau |date=June 18, 2019 |title=Xgau Sez |url=https://robertchristgau.com/xgausez.php?d=2019-06-18 |access-date=June 19, 2019 |website=robertchristgau.com |archive-date=October 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019012225/https://robertchristgau.com/xgausez.php?d=2019-06-18 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another ''Billboard'' spokesperson told [[Genius (website)|Genius]], "''Billboard''{{'}}s decision to take the song off of the country chart had absolutely nothing to do with the race of the artist."<ref name="Nast" /> Despite being removed from the main Country Songs chart, the song charted on ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s [[Country Airplay]] chart, debuting at 53,<ref name="billboard.com">{{Cite magazine |date=April 9, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X's 'Old Town Road' Debuts on Country Airplay Chart, Driven by Morning Show Spins |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8506437/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-country-airplay-chart-debut |magazine=Billboard |access-date=April 29, 2019 |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430121344/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8506437/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-country-airplay-chart-debut |url-status=live }}</ref> and peaking at 50.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=January 2, 2013 |title=Country Radio Music Chart |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/country-airplay |magazine=Billboard |access-date=April 29, 2019 |archive-date=November 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201114194457/https://www.billboard.com/charts/country-airplay |url-status=live }}</ref> In response, [[Sony Music Nashville]] CEO Randy Goodman told ''Billboard'' that his team started testing the song in some country radio markets, adding "it would be negligent not to look at it".<ref name="billboard.com" /> In May 2019, the issues of racism in country music culture came up again when [[Wrangler (jeans)|Wrangler]] announced its Lil Nas X collection, and some consumers threatened a boycott.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Nittle |first=Nadra |date=June 5, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X isn't an anomaly — black people have always been a part of country music |url=https://www.vox.com/the-goods/2019/6/5/18653880/lil-nas-x-country-music-billboard-wrangler-old-town-road |access-date=July 12, 2019 |website=Vox |language=en |archive-date=June 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616091732/https://www.vox.com/the-goods/2019/6/5/18653880/lil-nas-x-country-music-billboard-wrangler-old-town-road |url-status=live }}</ref> Media outlets also noted that the song brings attention to the historic cultural erasure of African-Americans from both [[country music]] and the [[American frontier]] era.<ref name=":6">{{Cite magazine |last=Sheffield |first=Rob |date=July 19, 2019 |title=The 'Old Town Road' Goes on Forever |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/old-town-road-lil-nas-x-yeehaw-manifesto-859566/ |magazine=Rolling Stone |language=en-US |access-date=July 19, 2019 |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720150250/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/old-town-road-lil-nas-x-yeehaw-manifesto-859566/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Ruckus |first=Jake Iverson |date=July 18, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X's "Old Town Road" highlights the forgotten Black history of country music |work=Bozeman Daily Chronicle |url=https://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/bozeman/lil-nas-x-s-old-town-road-highlights-the-forgotten/article_a85afe73-fc08-59d2-b426-ed76048ac246.html |access-date=July 20, 2019 |language=en |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720050624/https://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/bozeman/lil-nas-x-s-old-town-road-highlights-the-forgotten/article_a85afe73-fc08-59d2-b426-ed76048ac246.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Weber |first=Jered |date=July 30, 2019 |title=The real 'Old Town Road': Lil Nas X highlights black cowboy culture across US |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2019/07/30/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-black-cowboy-culture/1801170001/ |access-date=August 1, 2019 |website=USA Today |language=en |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731013802/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2019/07/30/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-black-cowboy-culture/1801170001/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Smith |first=Jordan-Marie |date=August 2, 2019 |title=Tracing Country Music's Roots Back to 17th-Century Slave Ships |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/08/02/tracing-country-musics-roots-back-th-century-slave-ships/ |access-date=August 3, 2019 |archive-date=August 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803123259/https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/08/02/tracing-country-musics-roots-back-th-century-slave-ships/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In an April 2019, country music star [[Billy Ray Cyrus]] was featured on a remix of "Old Town Road", the first of several.<ref name=":12">{{Cite news |last=Sisario |first=Ben |date=April 5, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Added Billy Ray Cyrus to 'Old Town Road.' Is It Country Enough for Billboard Now? |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/05/business/media/lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-billboard.html |access-date=April 5, 2019 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=April 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405194605/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/05/business/media/lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-billboard.html |url-status=live }}</ref>{{efn|The single's second official remix, "Old Town Road" (Diplo Remix), was released on April 29, 2019, featuring additional production by American DJ [[Diplo]].<ref name="Boot">{{Cite web |last=Angela Stefano |date=April 29, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X, Billy Ray Cyrus + Diplo Reveal Another 'Old Town Road' Remix at Stagecoach 2019 [WATCH] |url=https://theboot.com/lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-diplo-old-town-road-remix-stagecoach-2019-watch/ |access-date=April 29, 2019 |website=The Boot |archive-date=July 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702013435/https://theboot.com/lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-diplo-old-town-road-remix-stagecoach-2019-watch/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Mid-July 2019, an official remix of "Old Town Road" was released adding rapper [[Young Thug]], and yodeler [[Mason Ramsey]], to Billy Ray Cyrus.<ref name=":2" /> In late July 2019, another remix called "Seoul Town Road" was released featuring South Korean rapper [[RM (rapper)|RM]] of the boyband [[BTS]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=France |first=Lisa Respers |date=July 25, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X and RM of BTS drop new 'Old Town Road' remix |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/25/entertainment/lil-nas-x-rm-old-town-trnd/index.html |access-date=July 25, 2019 |publisher=CNN |language=en |archive-date=July 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725143429/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/25/entertainment/lil-nas-x-rm-old-town-trnd/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Billboard'' counts all the versions of the song in the same total.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Roberts |first=Randall |date=July 12, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X and Billie Eilish enlist array of stars in all-out race for No. 1 |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-eilish-bieber-lil-nas-x-young-thug-hot-100-20190712-story.html |access-date=July 13, 2019 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |archive-date=July 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712172246/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-eilish-bieber-lil-nas-x-young-thug-hot-100-20190712-story.html |url-status=live }}</ref>}} That same month, Lil Nas X broke [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]'s record for the most U.S. streams from one song in one week with 143 million streams for the week ending April 11, surpassing Drake's "[[In My Feelings]]" which had 116.2&nbsp;million streams in a week in July 2018;<ref>{{Cite web |title=Lil Nas X's "Old Town Road" Breaks Drake's Streaming Record! |url=http://top40-charts.com/news.php?nid=146014 |access-date=April 16, 2019 |website=Top40-Charts.com |archive-date=June 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626183005/https://top40-charts.com/news.php?nid=146014 |url-status=live }}</ref> as of August 2019 it has [[Music streaming|streamed]] over a billion plays on [[Spotify]] alone.<ref name=":8" /> In May 2019, the video was released and as of August 2019, has over 370 million views.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=France |first=Lisa Resper |date=July 12, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X blesses us with a new 'Old Town Road' remix |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/12/entertainment/lil-nas-x-old-town-remix/index.html |access-date=July 13, 2019 |website=CNN Entertainment |language=en |archive-date=July 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712221323/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/12/entertainment/lil-nas-x-old-town-remix/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":10">{{Cite web |last=Sloan |first=Elizabeth |date=August 26, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X's Real Name Is Montero Lamar Hill |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/08/lil-nas-x-real-name/ |access-date=August 29, 2019 |website=Heavy |archive-date=August 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829084623/https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/08/lil-nas-x-real-name/ |url-status=live }}</ref> [[NBC News]]'s Michael Arceneaux wrote, "In the social media age, Lil Nas X is arguably the first micro-platform crossover star."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Arceneaux |first=Michael |date=July 14, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X showed Billboard and his critics that they can't tell him nothin' |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/lil-nas-x-showed-billboard-his-critics-they-can-t-ncna1029411 |access-date=July 15, 2019 |publisher=NBC News |language=en |archive-date=July 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715045013/https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/lil-nas-x-showed-billboard-his-critics-they-can-t-ncna1029411 |url-status=live }}</ref>

"[[Panini (song)|Panini]]" was released as Lil Nas X's second single through [[Columbia Records]] on June 20, 2019.<ref name="Saponara2">{{Cite magazine |last=Saponara |first=Michael |date=June 20, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Releases 'Panini' Ahead of New EP '7' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8516834/lil-nas-x-releases-panini-listen |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=June 20, 2019 |archive-date=June 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630234950/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8516834/lil-nas-x-releases-panini-listen |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Williams |first=Aaron |date=June 20, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Contemplates The Price Of Fame On 'Panini' From His Upcoming Debut EP |url=https://uproxx.com/hiphop/lil-nas-x-panini/ |access-date=June 20, 2019 |website=[[Uproxx]] |archive-date=June 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620165330/https://uproxx.com/hiphop/lil-nas-x-panini/ |url-status=live }}</ref> It is named after the fictional [[cabbit]] bear of the same name in the animated television series ''[[Chowder (TV series)|Chowder]]'',<ref name="CNNPanini">{{Cite web |last=Trammell |first=Kendall |date=June 20, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X's new song just made the panini far greater than a sandwich |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/20/entertainment/lil-nas-x-panini-new-song-trnd/index.html |access-date=June 24, 2019 |publisher=CNN |archive-date=June 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623211809/https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/20/entertainment/lil-nas-x-panini-new-song-trnd/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> and does not refer to [[Panini (sandwich)|the sandwich of the same name]]. In September 2019, "Panini" had its first remix released with rapper [[DaBaby]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bloom |first=Madison |date=September 13, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X and DaBaby Share New "Panini" Remix |work=Pitchfork |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/lil-nas-x-and-dababy-share-new-panini-remix-listen/ |access-date=September 13, 2019 |archive-date=September 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913221016/https://pitchfork.com/news/lil-nas-x-and-dababy-share-new-panini-remix-listen/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Lil Nas X released his second [[extended play]], titled ''[[7 (Lil Nas X EP)|7]]'', on June 21, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Lil Nas X on Instagram: '"7" the EP! next month. {{popdf}}🤩' |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BxnZJ8HHxMJ/ |access-date=June 26, 2019 |website=Instagram |archive-date=June 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626183008/https://www.instagram.com/p/BxnZJ8HHxMJ/ |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2024}}<ref>{{Cite web |title=Lil Nas X: 7 EP |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/lil-nas-x-7-ep/ |access-date=June 26, 2019 |website=Pitchfork |archive-date=June 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621075701/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/lil-nas-x-7-ep/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The EP debuted at number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart.<ref name="BB7">{{Cite magazine |last=Caulfield |first=Keith |date=June 30, 2019 |title=The Raconteurs Land First No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'Help Us Stranger' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8518137/the-raconteurs-first-no-1-album-billboard-200 |magazine=Billboard |access-date=July 1, 2019 |archive-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227092258/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8518137/the-raconteurs-first-no-1-album-billboard-200 |url-status=live }}</ref> On June 23, 2019, Lil Nas X performed with Cyrus at the [[2019 BET Awards]].<ref>{{Citation |last=BETNetworks |title=Lil Nas X & Billy Ray Cyrus Bring The Old Town Road To The BET Awards Live! {{!}} BET Awards 2019 |date=June 23, 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=amhC8WYgNA4 |access-date=June 24, 2019 |archive-date=December 25, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211225094541/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=amhC8WYgNA4 |url-status=live }}</ref> On June 30, Lil Nas X made his international debut at the largest greenfield festival in the world, the UK's annual [[Glastonbury Festival]], when he and Billy Ray Cyrus made a surprise appearance and joined [[Miley Cyrus]] for the song, before performing "Panini" solo in a set seen nationally on [[BBC]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Arcand |first=Rob |date=June 30, 2019 |title=Watch Miley Cyrus Bring Out Lil Nas X and Billy Ray Cyrus to Play 'Old Town Road' at Glastonbury |url=https://www.spin.com/2019/06/miley-cyrus-brings-out-lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-old-town-road-glastonbury-2019/ |magazine=Spin (magazine)|access-date=July 11, 2019 |archive-date=October 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201017085659/https://www.spin.com/2019/06/miley-cyrus-brings-out-lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-old-town-road-glastonbury-2019/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On the same day, Lil Nas X became one of the most visible Black [[queer]] male singers when he [[came out]] as gay.<ref name="LATout">{{Cite web |last=Kennedy |first=Gerrick D. |date=July 31, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X came out, but has hip-hop? A macho culture faces a crossroads |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2019-07-30/lil-nas-x-black-queer-men-hip-hop |access-date=August 1, 2019 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |language=en-US |archive-date=August 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801002057/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2019-07-30/lil-nas-x-black-queer-men-hip-hop |url-status=live }}</ref> This was especially significant for an artist in the country and hip hop genres, both of which emphasize [[machismo]] and "historically snubbed queer artists".<ref name="LATout" />{{efn|[[Rap]] is full of [[gay slur]]s like "sus", "[[No homo]]", and "Pause" using "queerness as a punchline".<ref name="LATout" />}}{{efn|Other notable Black queer men who gained mainstream acceptance before Lil Nas X include: [[Frank Ocean]]; [[Tyler, the Creator]]; [[ILoveMakonnen]]; [[Brockhampton (band)|Brockhampton]] frontman [[Kevin Abstract]]; and [[Steve Lacy]].<ref name="LATout" /> Black queer women artists have been accepted more readily,<ref name="LATout" /> while the [[queer hip hop]] movement goes back to the 1990s.<ref name="429mag">{{Cite web |url=http://dot429.com/articles/1645-homo-hop-is-dead-queer-hip-hop-is-the-real-deal |title=Homo Hop is dead, Queer hip hop is the real deal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317020626/http://dot429.com/articles/1645-homo-hop-is-dead-queer-hip-hop-is-the-real-deal |archive-date=March 17, 2013 |website=429 Magazine |date=March 11, 2013}}</ref>}} ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' premiered the [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]] in early July with three Lil Nas X songs: "[[Rodeo (Lil Nas X and Cardi B song)|Rodeo]]" with [[Cardi B]] at number nine; "Panini" at four; and "Old Town Road" as the first-ever number-one song on the chart.<ref name=":7">{{Cite magazine |date=July 2, 2019 |title=RS Charts: Lil Nas X's 'Old Town Road' Is Number One on Rolling Stone Top 100 Chart |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/rs-charts-top-100-lil-nas-x-shawn-mendes-drake-847955/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=July 3, 2019 |archive-date=July 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703221816/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/rs-charts-top-100-lil-nas-x-shawn-mendes-drake-847955/ |url-status=live }}</ref>{{efn|The [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]] tracks "the most popular songs of the week in the United States"; ranked by combining streams and sales, omitting radio plays.<ref name=":7" />}}

On August 19, 2019, Lil Nas X opened for Katy Perry at a concert Amazon held for its employees to celebrate its Prime Day sale.<ref name="PrimeDayConcert">{{Cite magazine |date=August 20, 2019 |title=Jeff Bezos shows up on stage at Amazon's epic employee concert, helps introduce Katy Perry |url=https://www.geekwire.com/2019/jeff-bezos-shows-stage-amazons-epic-employee-concert-helps-introduce-katy-perry/ |magazine=[[GeekWire]] |access-date=October 28, 2022 |archive-date=October 28, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221028222844/https://www.geekwire.com/2019/jeff-bezos-shows-stage-amazons-epic-employee-concert-helps-introduce-katy-perry/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

===2020–2021: ''Montero''===
On July 7, 2020, Lil Nas X revealed that his debut album was "almost finished". He also stated that he was working on a [[mixtape]], and invited producers to submit their beats for his new music.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Clarke |first=Patrick |date=July 7, 2020 |title=Lil Nas X says new album is 'almost finished' and that he's also working on a mixtape |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/lil-nas-x-says-new-album-is-almost-finished-and-that-hes-also-working-on-a-mixtape-2703240?amp |access-date=July 9, 2020 |website=[[NME]] |archive-date=July 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200708194838/https://www.nme.com/news/music/lil-nas-x-says-new-album-is-almost-finished-and-that-hes-also-working-on-a-mixtape-2703240?amp |url-status=live }}</ref> On November 8, 2020, he announced a new single, "[[Holiday (Lil Nas X song)|Holiday]]", which was released on November 13.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Minsker |first=Evan |date=November 8, 2020 |title=Watch Lil Nas X announce his new single "Holiday" |work=Pitchfork |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-lil-nas-x-announce-new-song-holiday-in-michael-j-fox-starring-ad/ |access-date=November 8, 2020 |archive-date=December 25, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211225094549/https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-lil-nas-x-announce-new-song-holiday-in-michael-j-fox-starring-ad/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On [[Roblox]], a virtual concert was held to promote Lil Nas X's single, with Lil Nas X-related items in the game's avatar shop.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kastrenakes |first=Jacob |date=November 10, 2020 |title=Lil Nas X brings Old Town Road to Roblox with an elaborate virtual concert |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/11/10/21557275/lil-nas-x-roblox-virtual-performance-announced-holiday-old-town-road |access-date=November 16, 2020 |website=The Verge |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116125219/https://www.theverge.com/2020/11/10/21557275/lil-nas-x-roblox-virtual-performance-announced-holiday-old-town-road |url-status=live }}</ref> The single debuted at 37 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, while the song's music video accumulated tens of millions of views within the first several weeks of release.

In January 2021, he released a children's book, ''C Is for Country''.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Lil Nas X Says Children Are His Core Audience Right Now, and That's OK |work=NPR.org |url=https://www.npr.org/2021/01/05/953349880/lil-nas-x-says-children-are-his-core-audience-right-now-and-thats-ok |access-date=January 11, 2021 |archive-date=January 10, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210110022029/https://www.npr.org/2021/01/05/953349880/lil-nas-x-says-children-are-his-core-audience-right-now-and-thats-ok |url-status=live }}</ref> The following month, he previewed his new song, "[[Montero (Call Me by Your Name)]]" in a [[Super Bowl LV]] commercial.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Kaufman |first=Gil |date=February 2, 2021 |title=Lil Nas X Previews New Song 'Montero (Call Me by Your Name)' in 2021 Super Bowl Ad: Watch |url=https://www.billboard.com/index.php/amp/articles/columns/hip-hop/9519863/lil-nas-x-2021-super-bowl-ad-logitech |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=February 8, 2021 |archive-date=December 25, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211225094557/https://www.billboard.com/music/rb-hip-hop/lil-nas-x-2021-super-bowl-ad-logitech-9519863/amp/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The song was officially released on March 26, 2021, along with an accompanying music video.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=March 26, 2021 |title=Lil Nas X Lap Dances in Hell, Gets Seduced in Garden of Eden in Trippy 'Montero' Video |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9546886/lil-nas-x-montero-video/ |magazine=Billboard |language=en |access-date=March 29, 2021 |archive-date=March 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210328235331/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9546886/lil-nas-x-montero-video |url-status=live }}</ref> On the same day, Lil Nas X revealed that his debut album would be named ''[[Montero (album)|Montero]]'', and that it would be released in mid-2021.<ref>{{Cite web |title="Montero" The Album Drops This Summer! |url=https://twitter.com/lilnasx/status/1375457886596333572 |access-date=March 26, 2021 |language=en |via=Twitter |archive-date=March 26, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210326144216/https://twitter.com/LilNasX/status/1375457886596333572 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2024}}{{Primary source inline|date=February 2023}} The video prompted strong reactions. The song was seen by many as a valuable expression of [[queer]]ness, though prominent conservative and Christian figures accused Lil Nas X of [[sacrilege]] and [[Satanism|devil worship]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Lil Nas X on His Provocative New Video for "Montero" |url=https://time.com/5950756/lil-nas-x-montero-interview/ |magazine=Time |access-date=March 29, 2021 |archive-date=March 29, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210329193110/https://time.com/5950756/lil-nas-x-montero-interview/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Dessem |first=Matthew |date=March 29, 2021 |title=Conservatives Are Enraged at Lil Nas X and His 'Satan Shoes' |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2021/03/lil-nas-x-montero-call-me-by-your-name-video-satan-lap-dance-shoes-human-blood-apology.html |access-date=March 29, 2021 |website=Slate |language=en |archive-date=March 30, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210330020105/https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2021/03/lil-nas-x-montero-call-me-by-your-name-video-satan-lap-dance-shoes-human-blood-apology.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite the controversy, "Montero (Call Me by Your Name)", debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, becoming Lil Nas X's second chart-topping single and third top-ten single.

On March 29, 2021, Lil Nas X partnered with New York-based art collective [[MSCHF]] to release a modified pair of [[Nike Air Max 97]]s called [[Satan Shoes]], which may be seen on Satan's feet in the music video used to promote the release of "Montero (Call Me by Your Name)".<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Holland |first1=Oscar |last2=Palumbo |first2=Jacqui |title=Lil Nas X's unofficial 'Satan' Nikes containing human blood sell out in under a minute |publisher=CNN |url=https://www.cnn.com/style/article/lil-nas-x-mschf-satan-nike-shoes/index.html |access-date=April 3, 2021 |archive-date=March 31, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210331013326/https://www.cnn.com/style/article/lil-nas-x-mschf-satan-nike-shoes/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=March 29, 2021 |title=Nike Sues Designer Behind Lil Nas X's "Satan Shoes" |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2122470/lil-nas-x-satan-shoes-nike-lawsuit/news/ |access-date=March 30, 2021 |website=Stereogum |archive-date=March 30, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210330001257/https://www.stereogum.com/2122470/lil-nas-x-satan-shoes-nike-lawsuit/news/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The shoes are black and red with a bronze pentagram, filled with "60cc and 1 drop of human blood". Only [[666 (number)|666]] pairs were made at a price of $1,018. [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] said they were uninvolved in the creation and promotion of the shoes and did not endorse the messages of Lil Nas X or MSCHF.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kiefer |first=Halle |date=April 1, 2021 |title=Nike Clarifies It Doesn't Endorse Lil Nas X's Satan Shoes, Now With Human Blood |url=https://www.vulture.com/2021/04/nike-dont-endorse-satan-shoes-lil-nas-x-posts-fake-apology.html |access-date=April 3, 2021 |website=Vulture |language=en-us |archive-date=May 31, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220531175100/https://www.vulture.com/2021/04/nike-dont-endorse-satan-shoes-lil-nas-x-posts-fake-apology.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The company filed a trademark lawsuit against MSCHF in New York federal court. On April 1, the judge issued a temporary restraining order blocking the sale and distribution of the shoes pending a preliminary injunction.<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 1, 2021 |title=Judge Orders Lil Nas X Satan Shoes off the Market for Now |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/judge-lil-nas-x-satan-shoes |access-date=April 3, 2021 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en |archive-date=May 3, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210503074013/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/judge-lil-nas-x-satan-shoes |url-status=live }}</ref> Lil Nas X responded to the lawsuit with a [[meme]] on Twitter showing himself as the character [[Squidward]], homeless and asking for money.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Nike Is Suing The Maker Of Lil Nas X's Satan Shoes |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/salvadorhernandez/lil-nas-x-satan-shoes-nike-lawsuit |access-date=March 30, 2021 |website=BuzzFeed News |date=March 30, 2021 |archive-date=March 30, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210330004117/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/salvadorhernandez/lil-nas-x-satan-shoes-nike-lawsuit |url-status=live }}</ref> Later, he released a prelude video for the song "[[Industry Baby]]", which stages a fake "Nike vs. Lil Nas X" trial in the Supreme Court, during which people discuss the [[Satan Shoes]] before condemning the singer for being gay.<ref>{{Citation |title=Lil Nas X – INDUSTRY BABY (Prelude) | date=July 19, 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5QLFrE2qSZo |access-date=May 8, 2022 |language=en |archive-date=May 9, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220509102224/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5QLFrE2qSZo |url-status=live }}</ref>

Following the controversies surrounding his previous song and its promotion, Lil Nas X released the more introspective single "[[Sun Goes Down (Lil Nas X song)|Sun Goes Down]]" on May 21, 2021,<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Legaspi |first=Althea |date=May 21, 2021 |title=Lil Nas X Helps Struggling Younger Version of Self in 'Sun Goes Down' Video |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lil-nas-x-sun-goes-down-song-video-1172737/ |url-status=live |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210521143520/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lil-nas-x-sun-goes-down-song-video-1172737/ |archive-date=May 21, 2021}}</ref> wherein he reflects on his struggles with bullying and coming to terms with his homosexuality in his upbringing.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mench |first=Chris |date=May 21, 2021 |title=Lil Nas X Addresses Suicidal Thoughts, Coming Out, & His History As A Barb On "Sun Goes Down" |url=https://genius.com/a/lil-nas-x-addresses-suicidal-thoughts-coming-out-his-history-as-a-barb-on-sun-goes-down |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210522000508/https://genius.com/a/lil-nas-x-addresses-suicidal-thoughts-coming-out-his-history-as-a-barb-on-sun-goes-down |archive-date=May 22, 2021 |website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]}}</ref> He performed the song alongside "Montero (Call Me by Your Name)" at ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' a day later, where he suffered a [[wardrobe malfunction]] during a [[pole dance]] routine when the seam of his trousers split, leaving him unable to finish it properly.<ref name="trousers">{{Cite web |last=Elan |first=Priya |date=May 23, 2021 |title=Lil Nas X's trousers split during Saturday Night Live |url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2021/may/23/lil-nas-xs-trousers-split-during-saturday-night-live |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210523130451/https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2021/may/23/lil-nas-xs-trousers-split-during-saturday-night-live |archive-date=May 23, 2021 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> On June 29, Lil Nas posted a promotional video of his debut album, ending it with ''Montero, the Album''. He also posted a snippet of a previously teased track called "[[Industry Baby]]".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Samuel |first=Ruth Etiesit |date=June 22, 2021 |title=The wait is nearly over: Lil Nas X tells fans his debut album is finally coming out |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2021-06-29/lil-nas-x-debut-album-finally-coming-out |url-status=live |access-date=May 4, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210706231114/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2021-06-29/lil-nas-x-debut-album-finally-coming-out |archive-date=July 6, 2021}}</ref> The song was released as a single on July 23, featuring rapper [[Jack Harlow]], with production by [[Kanye West]] and [[Take a Daytrip]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Romano |first=Nick |date=July 23, 2021 |title=Lil Nas X and his cellmates dance naked in a prison shower in new 'Industry Baby' video |url=https://ew.com/music/lil-nas-x-dances-naked-in-industry-baby-prison-video/ |url-status=live |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210723051442/https://ew.com/music/lil-nas-x-dances-naked-in-industry-baby-prison-video/ |archive-date=July 23, 2021 |access-date=May 4, 2023}}</ref> The song debuted at number two on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and reached number one on the chart for the ending week of October 23, 2021, becoming Lil Nas X's fourth top-ten single and third number one.

On September 17, 2021, ''Montero'' was released, along with its fourth single, "[[Thats What I Want]]".<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=September 17, 2021 |title=Lil Nas X Gives Birth to Long-Awaited Debut Album 'Montero': Stream It Now |url=http://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/news/pride/9631111/lil-nas-x-montero-listen |magazine=Billboard |access-date=September 20, 2021 |archive-date=September 20, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210920113043/https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/news/pride/9631111/lil-nas-x-montero-listen |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Langford |first=Jackson |date=September 17, 2021 |title=Watch Lil Nas X walk down the aisle in video for 'That's What I Want' |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-lil-nas-x-walk-down-the-aisle-in-video-for-thats-what-i-want-3048087 |access-date=September 18, 2021 |website=[[NME]] |archive-date=March 21, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220321071234/https://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-lil-nas-x-walk-down-the-aisle-in-video-for-thats-what-i-want-3048087 |url-status=live }}</ref> On October 23, 2021, Lil Nas X made a surprise appearance at [[Diplo]]'s set at Electronic Daisy Carnival Las Vegas. During the appearance he performed "Industry Baby", "Montero (Call Me by Your Name)", and "Old Town Road".<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Sheckells |first=Melinda |date=October 25, 2021 |title=Lil Nas X, Alison Wonderland, Cooler Temps & Less Sunlight: 10 Key Moments From EDC Las Vegas 2021 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/9650685/edc-las-vegas-2021-recap-highlights/ |magazine=Billboard |access-date=October 27, 2021 |archive-date=October 26, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211026220624/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/9650685/edc-las-vegas-2021-recap-highlights |url-status=live }}</ref>

On April 26, 2022, he announced his first [[concert tour]], the [[Long Live Montero Tour]]. The tour was in support of ''Montero'', and began in September 2022 and ran through January 2023.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Aswad |first=Jem |date=April 26, 2022 |title=Lil Nas X Unveils Dates for His First-Ever Tour, 'Long Live Montero' |language=en-US |url=https://variety.com/2022/music/news/lil-nas-x-long-live-montero-tour-dates-1235241037/ |access-date=April 26, 2022 |archive-date=April 26, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220426153619/https://variety.com/2022/music/news/lil-nas-x-long-live-montero-tour-dates-1235241037/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

===2022–present: ''Dreamboy'' and ''Nasarati 2'' mixtape===
On March 16, 2022, Lil Nas X returned from his hiatus, and teased two songs from his "almost finished" new album, "[[Late to da Party]]" featuring [[YoungBoy Never Broke Again]], and "Down Souf Hoes" featuring [[Saucy Santana]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ruth |first=Wolfgang |date=March 16, 2022 |title=Lil Nas X Is Back From Maternity Leave |url=https://www.vulture.com/2022/03/lil-nas-x-is-back-twitter-maternity-leave.html |access-date=March 27, 2022 |website=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]] |archive-date=March 22, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220322154848/https://www.vulture.com/2022/03/lil-nas-x-is-back-twitter-maternity-leave.html |url-status=live }}</ref> He also posted a preview of the track "Lean on My Body".<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Daw |first=Stephen |date=March 17, 2022 |title=Lil Nas X Strips Down (Literally) to Tease New Song 'Lean On My Body' |url=https://www.billboard.com/culture/pride/lil-nas-x-lean-on-my-body-teaser-tiktok-1235045439/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=March 27, 2022 |archive-date=March 27, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220327113334/https://www.billboard.com/culture/pride/lil-nas-x-lean-on-my-body-teaser-tiktok-1235045439/ |url-status=live }}</ref> "Late to da Party" was eventually released as a single on June 24, 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Lil Nas X & YoungBoy Never Broke Again – Late To The Party |url=https://forms.sonymusicfans.com/campaign/67248980133/ |access-date=June 18, 2022 |website=Sony Music Fans |language=en-US |archive-date=June 18, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220618022736/https://forms.sonymusicfans.com/campaign/67248980133/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Rettig |first=James |date=June 24, 2022 |title=Lil Nas X – "Late To Da Party" (Feat. NBA YoungBoy) |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2191200/lil-nas-x-late-to-da-party-nba-youngboy/music/ |access-date=June 24, 2022 |website=[[Stereogum]] |archive-date=June 24, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220624040934/https://www.stereogum.com/2191200/lil-nas-x-late-to-da-party-nba-youngboy/music/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1545466163588608000 |user=LilNasX |title=ltdp not a lead single, who said thst |date=July 8, 2022 |access-date=May 4, 2023 |url=https://twitter.com/lilnasx/status/1545466163588608000 |via=Twitter}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2024}} Lil Nas X said that the album would be "something fun, something for the summertime, something for the girls to get ready and party to".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Murray |first=Robin |date=June 4, 2022 |title=Lil Nas X Says His Second Album Is 'Something For The Summertime' |url=https://www.clashmusic.com/news/lil-nas-x-says-his-second-album-is-something-for-the-summertime#:~:text=Lil%20Nas%20X%20says%20his%20second%20album%20will%20be%20%22something,of%20the%20Las%20Vegas%20ceremony. |access-date=June 24, 2022 |website=[[Clash Magazine]] |archive-date=June 24, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220624230359/https://www.clashmusic.com/news/lil-nas-x-says-his-second-album-is-something-for-the-summertime#:~:text=Lil%20Nas%20X%20says%20his%20second%20album%20will%20be%20%22something,of%20the%20Las%20Vegas%20ceremony. |url-status=live }}</ref>

On his ''Long Live Montero Tour'', Lil Nas X performed his then-unreleased single "[[Star Walkin']]" and the intro to "Down Souf Hoes". On September 15, 2022, [[Riot Games]], the developers of the video game [[League of Legends]], announced a collaboration with Lil Nas X for the [[2022 League of Legends World Championship]] through a press release, where they also declared him to be "President of League of Legends", in what [[Kotaku]] journalist Isaiah Colbert called a publicity stunt.<ref name="Kotaku">{{Cite news |last=Colbert |first=Isaiah |date=September 15, 2022 |title=Um, Lil Nas X Is Now President Of League Of Legends |work=Kotaku |url=https://kotaku.com/lil-nas-x-riot-games-league-world-championship-song-1849540621 |access-date=September 23, 2022 |archive-date=September 23, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220923101250/https://kotaku.com/lil-nas-x-riot-games-league-world-championship-song-1849540621 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Marshall |first=Cass |date=September 15, 2022 |title=Lil Nas X will perform this year's League of Legends Worlds anthem, design a new skin |work=Polygon |url=https://www.polygon.com/23354828/lil-nas-x-league-of-legends-worlds-anthem-star-walkin-ksante-skin |access-date=September 23, 2022 |archive-date=September 23, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220923101254/https://www.polygon.com/23354828/lil-nas-x-league-of-legends-worlds-anthem-star-walkin-ksante-skin |url-status=live }}</ref> The anthem for the tournament, "Star Walkin'", was released on September 22 with an accompanying animated music video.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Marshall |first=Cass |date=September 22, 2022 |title=Lil Nas X's new League of Legends anthem Star Walkin' comes with a mecha music video |work=Polygon |url=https://www.polygon.com/23366879/lil-nas-x-star-walkin-song-league-of-legends-worlds-anthem-2022-video |access-date=September 23, 2022 |archive-date=September 23, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220923102756/https://www.polygon.com/23366879/lil-nas-x-star-walkin-song-league-of-legends-worlds-anthem-2022-video |url-status=live }}</ref> He performed the song at the opening ceremony of the tournament on November 5. Additionally, a custom outfit for a playable character in the game co-designed by Lil Nas X was temporarily made available in November.<ref name="Kotaku" />

On October 19, 2022, Lil Nas X invited Saucy Santana on his tour to perform the intro of "Down Souf Hoes" with an additional previously unheard verse.<ref>{{Citation |title=Lil Nas X performing Down Souf Hoes with Saucy Santana at YouTube Theater | date=October 20, 2022 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IIwWLqoIGbM |access-date=January 29, 2023 |language=en |archive-date=January 29, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230129182312/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IIwWLqoIGbM |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 17, 2023, Lil Nas X performed an extended play of the intro of the song during his [[Lollapalooza]] Chile performance.<ref>{{Citation |title=Lil Nas X - Down Souf Hoes (Snippet 4) | date=March 18, 2023 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XtYRcD6KK8g |access-date=May 13, 2023 |language=en |archive-date=May 13, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230513044244/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XtYRcD6KK8g |url-status=live }}</ref>

''[[Lil Nas X: Long Live Montero]]'', a documentary film by Carlos López Estrada and Zac Manuel, premiered at the [[2023 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hipes |first=Patrick |date=August 18, 2023 |title=Lil Nas X Doc 'Lil Nas X: Long Live Montero' To World Premiere At Toronto Film Festival |url=https://deadline.com/2023/08/lil-nas-x-long-live-montero-movie-premiere-toronto-film-festival-1235522234/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230818172621/https://deadline.com/2023/08/lil-nas-x-long-live-montero-movie-premiere-toronto-film-festival-1235522234/ |archive-date=August 18, 2023 |access-date=December 2, 2023 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |language=en-US}}</ref> The premiere was delayed by roughly half an hour because of a [[bomb threat]] from a caller who supposedly targeted Lil Nas X for being a black queer artist.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnelly |first1=Matt |last2=Jackson |first2=Angelique |title=Lil Nas X Doc Premiere at TIFF Delayed by Bomb Threat From Homophobic Caller (EXCLUSIVE) |url=https://variety.com/2023/film/news/lil-nas-x-documentary-premiere-tiff-bomb-threat-1235718996/ |work=Variety |date=September 10, 2023}}</ref> However, according to a spokesperson for the festival, "To our knowledge, this was a general threat and not directed at the film or the artist." The threat was ultimately proven to not be credible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2023/film/news/lil-nas-x-documentary-premiere-tiff-bomb-threat-1235718996/|title=Lil Nas X Doc Premiere at TIFF Delayed by Bomb Threat From Homophobic Caller (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=September 9, 2023|access-date=September 10, 2023|archive-date=September 10, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230910093020/https://variety.com/2023/film/news/lil-nas-x-documentary-premiere-tiff-bomb-threat-1235718996/|url-status=live}}</ref>

On January 3, 2024, Lil Nas X announced the single "[[J Christ]]", which was released on January 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2024/01/03/lil-nas-x-announces-new-single-and-video-dropping-next-week/|title=Lil Nas X Announces New Single And Video Dropping Next Week: "Y'all Ready For A Show?"|last=Trapp|first=Malcolm|website=[[Rap-Up]]|date=January 3, 2024|access-date=January 8, 2024|archive-date=January 8, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240108170313/https://www.rap-up.com/2024/01/03/lil-nas-x-announces-new-single-and-video-dropping-next-week/|url-status=live}}</ref> His next single, "Where Do We Go Now", was released on January 26, 2024, along with the streaming release of the documentary ''[[Lil Nas X: Long Live Montero]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/culture/pride/lil-nas-x-where-do-we-go-now-listen-1235589750/|title=Lil Nas X Is Ready for Something New on Reflective 'Where Do We Go Now': Stream It Now|last=Daw|first=Stephen|magazine=Billboard|date=January 26, 2024|access-date=February 10, 2024}}</ref>

Lil Nas X was featured on [[Camila Cabello]]'s single "[[He Knows]]" which was released on May 10, 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/cmalone/2024/05/10/camila-cabello-and-lil-nas-x-team-up-for-new-single-he-knows/?sh=757dc02c4271|title=Camila Cabello And Lil Nas X Team Up For New Single 'He Knows'|website=Forbes}}</ref>

==Musical style and influences==
Lil Nas X's musical style has been described as [[hip hop]],<ref name="Allmusic genre">{{Cite web |last=Yeung |first=Neil |title=Lil Nas X Bio |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/lil-nas-x-mn0003827666/biography |access-date=September 20, 2019 |website=[[AllMusic]] |archive-date=June 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200620071016/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/lil-nas-x-mn0003827666/biography |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=August 12, 2021 |title=How Lil Nas X is revolutionizing hip-hop as an empowered gay star |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-pop-culture/lil-nas-x-revolutionizing-hip-hop-empowered-gay-star-rcna1661 |access-date=September 20, 2021 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |archive-date=September 20, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210920011742/https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-pop-culture/lil-nas-x-revolutionizing-hip-hop-empowered-gay-star-rcna1661 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="LOBF genres">{{Cite web |last=Magan |first=Valerie |date=June 28, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X's 7 EP shows room for growth... but not much else |url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/reviews/albums/lil-nas-x-7-ep-album-review |access-date=June 19, 2021 |website=[[The Line of Best Fit]] |archive-date=June 24, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210624203222/https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/reviews/albums/lil-nas-x-7-ep-album-review |url-status=live }}</ref> [[pop rap]],<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Sidney Madden |last2=Jonaki Mehta |last3=Mallory Yu |date=September 17, 2021 |title=The Learning Curve Of Lil Nas X |url=https://www.npr.org/2021/09/17/1038236814/the-learning-curve-of-lil-nas-x |access-date=September 20, 2021 |publisher=[[NPR]] |archive-date=September 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210919215150/https://www.npr.org/2021/09/17/1038236814/the-learning-curve-of-lil-nas-x |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Harris |first=Tanner |date=September 20, 2021 |title=Album Review: Lil Nas X's 'Montero' is breaking the barriers of what pop-rap can be |url=https://www.thepostathens.com/article/2021/09/lil-nas-x-montero-album-review-lgbtq |access-date=September 20, 2021 |website=The Post Athens |archive-date=September 21, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210921050347/https://www.thepostathens.com/article/2021/09/lil-nas-x-montero-album-review-lgbtq |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Torres |first=Eric |date=September 20, 2021 |title=Lil Nas X: Montero Album Review |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/lil-nas-x-montero/ |access-date=September 20, 2021 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |archive-date=September 21, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210921012919/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/lil-nas-x-montero/ |url-status=live }}</ref> [[country rap]],<ref>{{Cite web |last=Trammell |first=Kendall |date=July 20, 2019 |title=Country rap is getting bigger, and Lil Nas X is leading the way |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/20/entertainment/lil-nas-x-country-rap-trnd/index.html |access-date=September 21, 2021 |publisher=[[CNN]] |archive-date=September 21, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210921003257/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/20/entertainment/lil-nas-x-country-rap-trnd/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Del Rosario |first=Alexandra |date=August 26, 2019 |title=VMAs: Lil Nas X Channels Robotic Future During "Panini" Performance |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lil-nas-x-performs-panini-a-2019-mtv-vmas-1234545 |access-date=September 14, 2019 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |language=en |archive-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827052820/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lil-nas-x-performs-panini-a-2019-mtv-vmas-1234545 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Jamieson |first=Brii |date=June 12, 2019 |title=Travis Barker Has Written A Song With Viral Country Rap Artist Lil Nas X |url=https://www.rocksound.tv/news/amp/travis-barker-is-in-the-studio-with-viral-country-rap-artist-lil-nas-x |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923215432/https://www.rocksound.tv/news/amp/travis-barker-is-in-the-studio-with-viral-country-rap-artist-lil-nas-x |archive-date=September 23, 2019 |access-date=September 14, 2019 |website=Rock Sound}}</ref> [[Trap music|trap]],<ref name="LOBF genres" /> [[pop rock]],<ref name="LOBF genres" /> pop,<ref name="LOBF genres" /><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Johnston |first=Maura |author-link=Maura Johnston |date=September 17, 2021 |title=Montero review: Lil Nas X sounds limitless on his debut album |url=https://ew.com/music/music-reviews/lil-nas-x-montero-review/ |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=September 20, 2021 |archive-date=September 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210919020056/https://ew.com/music/music-reviews/lil-nas-x-montero-review/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and rock.<ref name="LOBF genres" />

He credits LGBTQ artists [[Frank Ocean]] and [[Tyler, the Creator]] as inspirations and for "making it easier for me to be where I am, comfortably."<ref>{{Cite news |last=Espinoza |first=Joshua |date=December 1, 2020 |title=Lil Nas X Says Tyler, the Creator and Frank Ocean 'Made It Easier for Me to Be Where I Am, Comfortably' |work=complex.com |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/12/lil-nas-x-tyler-the-creator-frank-ocean-influence |access-date=May 29, 2021 |archive-date=May 17, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220517083448/https://www.complex.com/music/2020/12/lil-nas-x-tyler-the-creator-frank-ocean-influence |url-status=live }}</ref> Lil Nas X also cites [[Nicki Minaj]], [[Katy Perry]], [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], [[Miley Cyrus]] and [[Doja Cat]] as some of his biggest influences.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Lil Nas X Says Miley Cyrus Doesn't 'Even Realize How Much of a Legend' She Is: 'I Really Admire Her' |url=https://people.com/music/lil-nas-x-says-miley-cyrus-doesnt-even-realize-how-much-of-a-legend-she-is/ |website=People |quote=...about two of his biggest inspirations |access-date=September 23, 2021 |archive-date=September 25, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210925103537/https://people.com/music/lil-nas-x-says-miley-cyrus-doesnt-even-realize-how-much-of-a-legend-she-is/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Lil Nas X on 'Montero (Call Me By Your Name),' forgiving himself, and being a Barb |url=https://ew.com/music/lil-nas-x-montero-pride-cover-story/ |magazine=Entertainment Weekly |language=en |access-date=September 21, 2021 |archive-date=September 18, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210918071607/https://ew.com/music/lil-nas-x-montero-pride-cover-story/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Lil Nas X Talks 'Montero' Album, Shawn Mendes & His Biggest Musical Impacts |url=https://elvisduran.iheart.com/featured/elvis-duran/content/2021-09-15-lil-nas-x-talks-montero-album-shawn-mendes-his-biggest-musical-impacts/ |website=[[Elvis Duran and the Morning Show]] |access-date=October 7, 2021 |archive-date=October 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211007041941/https://elvisduran.iheart.com/featured/elvis-duran/content/2021-09-15-lil-nas-x-talks-montero-album-shawn-mendes-his-biggest-musical-impacts/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019 he said, "I grew up off the Internet, so my influences come from all over musically." He grew up listening to hip hop artists such as [[Andre 3000]], [[Kendrick Lamar]], [[Kid Cudi]], and [[Lil Uzi Vert]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Eells |first=Josh |date=May 20, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X: Inside the Rise of a Hip-Hop Cowboy |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-interview-new-album-836393/ |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=May 20, 2019 |archive-date=July 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702014754/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-interview-new-album-836393/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Chesman |first=Donna-Claire |date=May 16, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Started Making Music Because He Was Bored |work=DJ Booth |url=https://djbooth.net/features/2019-05-16-lil-nas-x-music-career-bored |access-date=May 29, 2021 |archive-date=June 2, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210602213154/https://djbooth.net/features/2019-05-16-lil-nas-x-music-career-bored |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Impact==

Lil Nas X's success caused him to become the first person of color and the first openly gay performer to be listed by ''[[Forbes]]'' in its annual Highest-Paid Country Acts List.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Greenburg |first=Zack O'Malley |date=November 13, 2019 |title=Highest-Paid Country Acts 2019: Lil Nas X Debuts; Luke Bryan Tops List |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2019/11/13/highest-paid-country-acts-2019-lil-nas-x-debuts-luke-bryan-tops-list/ |access-date=December 4, 2019 |website=Forbes |language=en |archive-date=December 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203134821/https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2019/11/13/highest-paid-country-acts-2019-lil-nas-x-debuts-luke-bryan-tops-list/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Telusma |first=Blue |date=December 3, 2019 |title=Lil Nax X' is first openly gay Black man to make Forbes' Highest Paid Country Acts list |url=https://thegrio.com/2019/12/03/lil-nas-x-becomes-1st-openly-gay-black-man-on-forbes-highest-paid-country-acts-list/ |access-date=December 4, 2019 |website=theGrio |language=en-US |archive-date=December 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204144559/https://thegrio.com/2019/12/03/lil-nas-x-becomes-1st-openly-gay-black-man-on-forbes-highest-paid-country-acts-list/ |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Ken Burns]], who produced the [[PBS]] documentary [[Country Music (miniseries)|''Country Music'']], noted,{{Blockquote|"Well, to me, Lil Nas X is my [[mic drop]] moment. We spend eight episodes and sixteen and a half hours talking about the fact that country music has never been one thing. ... And there's a huge African American influence, and it permeates throughout the whole story. ... And here we are in a new modern age that we're not touching, with all these classic, binary arguments about ''Billboard'' not listing ['Old Town Road'] on the country chart, and it turns out to be not just the No. 1 country hit but the No. 1 ''single'', period, and it's by a black gay rapper! ... It just is proving that all of those cycles that we have been reporting on across the decades—all of the tensions in country music of race, class, poverty, gender, creativity versus commerce, geography—are still going on."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=September 15, 2019 |title=Ken Burns on 'Country Music' and Why Merle, Hank, Dwight, Loretta and Lil Nas X Matter |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/ken-burns-interview-country-music-1203336019/ |access-date=September 17, 2019 |website=Variety |language=en |archive-date=September 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916012237/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/ken-burns-interview-country-music-1203336019/ |url-status=live }}</ref>}}

Following the release of the music video for "[[Montero (Call Me by Your Name)]]", several outlets praised Lil Nas X for his "unabashedly queer" visuals.<ref name="unabashedly">{{Cite magazine|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|date=March 26, 2021|title=Lil Nas X Shares Unabashedly Queer Video for 'Montero (Call Me By Your Name)'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lil-nas-x-call-me-by-your-name-1146925/|url-status=live|access-date=March 26, 2021|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|language=en-US|archive-date=March 26, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210326141915/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lil-nas-x-call-me-by-your-name-1146925/}}</ref><ref name="changed">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2021/music/news/lil-nas-x-montero-queer-music-artists-sexuality-1234939238/|title=Lil Nas X's Sexed-Up 'Montero' Video Has Changed Everything for Queer Music Artists|date=March 26, 2021|first=Adam B.|last=Vary|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=March 27, 2021|archive-date=March 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210327003627/https://variety.com/2021/music/news/lil-nas-x-montero-queer-music-artists-sexuality-1234939238/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/culture/lil-nas-x-montero-music-video|title=Lil Nas X's "Montero" Is an Encouraging Note to Self|date=March 26, 2021|first=Brooke|last=Marine|work=[[W (magazine)|W]]|access-date=March 27, 2021|archive-date=March 29, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210329131509/https://www.wmagazine.com/culture/lil-nas-x-montero-music-video|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'s}} Adam B. Vary wrote that the video "changed everything for queer music artists", noting that some LGBT artists like [[Jonathan Knight]] of [[New Kids on the Block]] and [[Lance Bass]] of [[NSYNC]] sang about women while staying [[closeted]], while others like [[Elton John]] and [[Ricky Martin]] did not explicitly sing about their sexuality.<ref name="changed" /> He described the sexual imagery, including the pole dance, as evoking images of Madonna or [[Janet Jackson]], without the need to hide his homosexuality.<ref name="changed" /> The negative reception to the song and music video was characterized by ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' and ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' as illustrating a [[Satanic panic]] and compared to past moments in popular music history, including jazz music being referred to as "the devil's music" in the early [[20th century music|20th century]], [[John Lennon]]'s comment in a 1966 interview that [[the Beatles]] were "[[more popular than Jesus]]", [[backmasking]] accusations, the [[Parents Music Resource Center]]'s "Filthy Fifteen", Madonna's music video for "[[Like a Prayer (song)|Like a Prayer]]", [[Lady Gaga]]'s music videos for "[[Judas (Lady Gaga song)|Judas]]" and "[[Alejandro (song)|Alejandro]]", and [[Nicki Minaj]]'s performance of "[[Roman Holiday (song)|Roman Holiday]]" at the [[54th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref name="vicesatanic">{{Cite web|last=Terry|first=Josh|date=March 29, 2021|title=Lil Nas X Isn't the First Pop Star to Spark a Satanic Panic|url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/jgqyxp/lil-nas-x-isnt-the-first-pop-star-to-spark-a-satanic-panic|website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|access-date=March 30, 2021|archive-date=May 16, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210516015723/https://www.vice.com/en/article/jgqyxp/lil-nas-x-isnt-the-first-pop-star-to-spark-a-satanic-panic|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2021-03-29/lil-nas-x-montero-satanic-panic|title=Lil Nas X's 'Montero' and the delight of yet another satanic panic|date=March 29, 2021|first=Mikael|last=Wood|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=March 30, 2021|archive-date=March 30, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210330003515/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2021-03-29/lil-nas-x-montero-satanic-panic|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Public image==
[[File:Glasto2023 (343 of 468) (53008939166).jpg|thumb|250px|Lil Nas X grabbing his crotch during his performance at the [[Glastonbury Festival 2023]]]]
Lil Nas X has been noted for his public fashions; in July 2019, [[Vogue (magazine)|''Vogue'']] noted Lil Nas X as a "master" at giving the cowboy [[aesthetic]] a glam look in his appearances and on [[Instagram]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hahn |first=Rachel |date=July 15, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Gives Cowboy Style a Very Glam Vegas Makeover |url=https://www.vogue.com/vogueworld/article/lil-nas-x-yeehaw-style-glam-cowboy-las-vegas-instagram |access-date=July 17, 2019 |website=Vogue |language=en |archive-date=July 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717025309/https://www.vogue.com/vogueworld/article/lil-nas-x-yeehaw-style-glam-cowboy-las-vegas-instagram |url-status=live }}</ref> His [[Wardrobe stylist|stylist]], Hodo Musa, says he aims for items that are "electric, playful, colorful, and futuristic."<ref name=":13">{{Cite web |last=Hahn |first=Rachel |date=August 29, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Takes on His Very First VMAs in Glam-Cowboy Style |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/lil-nas-x-2019-vmas-panini-christian-cowan-video |access-date=August 30, 2019 |website=Vogue |archive-date=August 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830112401/https://www.vogue.com/article/lil-nas-x-2019-vmas-panini-christian-cowan-video |url-status=live }}</ref> For his onstage look at the [[2019 MTV Video Music Awards]] he wore a cowboy motif cherry-red [[Nudie suit]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gallagher |first=Jacob |date=September 9, 2019 |title=From Roy Rogers to Lil Nas X: The Wild Western Story of Nudie Suits |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/from-roy-rogers-to-lil-nas-x-the-wild-western-story-of-nudie-suits-11568047012 |access-date=September 9, 2019 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |archive-date=September 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190909195046/https://www.wsj.com/articles/from-roy-rogers-to-lil-nas-x-the-wild-western-story-of-nudie-suits-11568047012 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Wrangler (jeans)|Wrangler]], which is mentioned in the "Old Town Road" lyrics, has consistently sold out of Lil Nas X co-branded fashions.<ref>{{Cite web |title='Old Town Road' boosts Wrangler jeans |url=https://www.messenger-inquirer.com/features/business/old-town-road-boosts-wrangler-jeans/article_7648e9c9-cfee-5de9-bf99-a27aa526a1e8.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813093809/https://www.messenger-inquirer.com/features/business/old-town-road-boosts-wrangler-jeans/article_7648e9c9-cfee-5de9-bf99-a27aa526a1e8.html |archive-date=August 13, 2019 |access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref>

For the [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards]] Lil Nas X wore several outfits including a [[Pink Versace Suit and Harness of Lil Nas X|head-to-toe couture fuchsia Versace suit with a pink harness]] that took 700 hours to construct.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tracer |first=Daniel |date=January 28, 2020 |title=WATCH: Lil Nas X's pink leather harness look took 700 hours to make |url=https://www.queerty.com/watch-lil-nas-xs-pink-leather-harness-look-took-700-hours-make-20200128 |access-date=February 1, 2020 |website=[[Queerty]] |archive-date=March 15, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230315175642/https://www.queerty.com/watch-lil-nas-xs-pink-leather-harness-look-took-700-hours-make-20200128 |url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2020, Lil Nas X modeled in a trailer video for a new skincare line by [[Rihanna]]'s [[Fenty Beauty]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hou |first=Kathleen |date=July 21, 2020 |title=Watch Rihanna Throw a Pool Party |url=https://www.thecut.com/2020/07/rihanna-throws-a-pool-party-with-lil-nas-x-for-fenty-skin.html |access-date=July 24, 2020 |website=[[New York Magazine|The Cut]] |archive-date=July 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200722071538/https://www.thecut.com/2020/07/rihanna-throws-a-pool-party-with-lil-nas-x-for-fenty-skin.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In August 2021, Lil Nas X commented "Nah he tweakin" on an [[Instagram]] post about [[Tony Hawk]] selling skateboards painted with paint that contained his blood. It became a [[viral phenomenon]] for the next few days.<ref>{{Cite web |date=August 26, 2021 |title=Nah he tweakin: What it means and why it's all over our timelines |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-58344467 |access-date=September 1, 2021 |publisher=BBC |archive-date=September 2, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210902011326/https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-58344467 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Mahan |first=Logan |date=August 30, 2021 |title=Why 'Nah He Tweakin' Is Suddenly Flooding Internet Comment Sections |url=https://www.insidehook.com/daily_brief/internet/nah-he-tweakin-lil-nas-x-tony-hawk-instagram-explainer |access-date=September 1, 2021 |website=insidehook.com |archive-date=September 2, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210902011327/https://www.insidehook.com/daily_brief/internet/nah-he-tweakin-lil-nas-x-tony-hawk-instagram-explainer |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2022, he was criticized for repeatedly grabbing his genitals, and placing his microphone at the center of his crotch and swinging it around, pretending the device was his [[Human penis|penis]], during his performance at the [[64th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 3, 2022 |title=Lil Nas X shocks Grammys with penis grabs, touts 'sex with a stranger' |url=https://nypost.com/2022/04/03/twitter-blasts-lil-nas-x-for-repeatedly-grabbing-his-crotch/ |access-date=May 27, 2023 |work=New York Post |archive-date=May 27, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230527224334/https://nypost.com/2022/04/03/twitter-blasts-lil-nas-x-for-repeatedly-grabbing-his-crotch/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=April 4, 2022 |title=And the Grammy for Onstage Penis Grabbing Goes to Lil Nas X |url=https://www.insidehook.com/daily_brief/music/grammy-onstage-penis-grabbing-lil-nas-x |access-date=May 27, 2023 |publisher=Inside Hook |archive-date=May 27, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230527224334/https://www.insidehook.com/daily_brief/music/grammy-onstage-penis-grabbing-lil-nas-x |url-status=live }}</ref>

In May 2023, Lil Nas X attended the [[Met Gala]] wearing only silver body paint, a [[thong]], and high-heeled platform shoes, with his face covered with [[rhinestone]]s. His look was inspired by the late German fashion icon [[Karl Lagerfeld]]'s cat Choupette.<ref>{{Cite news |date=May 2, 2023 |title=17 Looks That Did the Most at the Met Gala |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/05/02/fashion/met-gala-best-fashion-photos-doja-cat-lil-nas-x.html |access-date=May 3, 2023 |archive-date=May 2, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230502232649/https://www.nytimes.com/2023/05/02/fashion/met-gala-best-fashion-photos-doja-cat-lil-nas-x.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In the lead-up to the release of his album ''Montero'', he hosted a fundraiser for several charities focused on AIDS/HIV prevention in the Southern US. The project raised nearly half a million dollars by March 2022.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/culture/pride/lil-nas-x-baby-registry-raises-half-million-hiv-prevention-1235050882/amp/|title=Lil Nas X's 'Baby Registry' Raised Almost Half a Million Dollars for HIV Prevention in Southern States|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] }}</ref>

==Personal life==
===Coming out===
In early June 2019, Lil Nas X [[came out]] to his sister and father and he felt "the universe was signalling him to do so", despite his uncertainty whether his fans would stick by him or not.<ref name=":8" /> On June 30, 2019, the last day of [[Pride Month]], Lil Nas X came out publicly as gay.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Minsker |first=Evan |date=July 1, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Comes Out as Gay |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/lil-nas-x-comes-out-as-gay/ |access-date=July 4, 2019 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |archive-date=July 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701091253/https://pitchfork.com/news/lil-nas-x-comes-out-as-gay/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Nordyke |first=Kimberly |date=June 30, 2019 |title=Rapper Lil Nas X Seemingly Comes Out as Gay |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/rapper-lil-nas-x-seemingly-comes-as-gay-1221935 |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=July 1, 2019 |archive-date=April 4, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210404163309/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/rapper-lil-nas-x-seemingly-comes-as-gay-1221935 |url-status=live }}</ref> His [[tweeting|tweet]] confirmed earlier suspicions when he first indicated this in his track "[[c7osure]]". ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' noted the song "touches on themes such as coming clean, growing up and embracing one's self".<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 1, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Comes Out On World Pride Day |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/lil-nas-x-comes-out-world-pride-day |access-date=July 13, 2019 |publisher=National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences |language=en |archive-date=July 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200716084239/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/lil-nas-x-comes-out-world-pride-day |url-status=live }}</ref> The next day he tweeted again, this time highlighting the [[Rainbow flag (LGBT movement)|rainbow-colored]] building on the cover art of [[7 (Lil Nas X EP)|his EP ''7'']], with the caption reading "deadass thought i made it obvious".<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Comes Out as Gay |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/lil-nas-x-comes-out-as-gay/ |access-date=July 2, 2019 |website=Pitchfork |archive-date=July 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701091253/https://pitchfork.com/news/lil-nas-x-comes-out-as-gay/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="USA Today">{{Cite web |last=Henderson |first=Cydney |title='Old Town Road' rapper Lil Nas X faces down homophobic comments after coming out |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2019/07/02/old-town-road-artist-lil-nas-x-faces-homophobia-after-coming-out/1632790001/ |access-date=July 2, 2019 |newspaper=USA Today |archive-date=May 9, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210509162728/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2019/07/02/old-town-road-artist-lil-nas-x-faces-homophobia-after-coming-out/1632790001/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He was unambiguous in an interview several days later on ''[[BBC Breakfast]]'', where he stated that he was gay and understands that his sexuality is not readily accepted in the country or rap music communities.<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 5, 2019 |title=Watch: In New Interview, Rapper Lil Nas X Says He's Faced Backlash After Coming Out as Gay |url=https://www.edgemedianetwork.com/entertainment/celebrities//278557 |access-date=July 7, 2019 |website=EDGE Media Network |language=en-us |archive-date=July 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707030445/https://www.edgemedianetwork.com/entertainment/celebrities//278557 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

The response to the news was mostly positive, but also garnered a large amount of [[homophobic]] backlash on social media, to which Lil Nas X also reacted.<ref name="USA Today" /><ref name="CapitalXtra">{{Cite web |title=Lil Nas X Responds To Homophobic Comments Following Sexuality Announcement |url=https://amp.capitalxtra.com/news/lil-nas-x-responds-homophobic-comments-sexuality/ |access-date=July 4, 2019 |website=amp.capitalxtra.com |archive-date=April 4, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210404163327/https://amp.capitalxtra.com/news/lil-nas-x-responds-homophobic-comments-sexuality/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The backlash also came from the hip hop community, drawing attention to [[homophobia in hip hop culture]].<ref name="CapitalXtra" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Marie |first=Aurielle |title=Beyond Expectations Lil Nas X Forges a Freer, More Fluid Hip Hop |url=https://www.bitchmedia.org/article/lil-nas-x-coming-out-challenges-hip-hop |access-date=July 12, 2019 |website=Bitch Media |archive-date=July 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712033200/https://www.bitchmedia.org/article/lil-nas-x-coming-out-challenges-hip-hop |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2020, rapper [[Pastor Troy]] made homophobic comments on the outfit Lil Nas X wore during the [[Grammy Award]]s, to which Lil Nas X responded: "Damn I look good in that pic on god."<ref>{{Cite web |date=January 30, 2020 |title=Lil Nas X Repsonds To Pastor Troy's Homophobic Rant In A Very Lil Nas X Way |url=https://www.vibe.com/news/entertainment/lil-nas-x-repsonds-to-pastor-troys-homophobic-rant-in-a-very-lil-nas-x-way-673631/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131093730/https://www.vibe.com/2020/01/lil-nas-x-repsonds-to-pastor-troys-homophobic-rant-in-a-very-lil-nas-x-way |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=December 2, 2023 |website=Vibe (magazine) |language=en-US}}</ref>

In January 2023, Lil Nas X tweeted a statement suggesting he was "a little [[bisexual]]."<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1612596434502815746|user=lilnasx|title=be fr would y'all be mad at me if i thought i was a little bisexual|first=Montero|last=Hill|author-link=Lil Nas X|date=January 9, 2023|access-date=January 15, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230111165932/https://twitter.com/LilNasX/status/1612596434502815746|archive-date=January 11, 2023|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Lil Nas X Tweets About Possibly Being 'A Little Bisexual' |url=https://www.out.com/celebs/2023/1/13/lil-nas-x-tweets-about-possibly-being-little-bisexual |access-date=February 12, 2023 |website=out.com |language=en |archive-date=February 12, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230212022329/https://www.out.com/celebs/2023/1/13/lil-nas-x-tweets-about-possibly-being-little-bisexual |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Lil Nas X Tweets About Possibly Being 'A Little Bisexual' |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/lil-nas-x-tweets-possibly-200420690.html |access-date=February 12, 2023 |publisher=Yahoo! Sport |date=January 13, 2023 |language=en-US |archive-date=February 12, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230212022337/https://sports.yahoo.com/lil-nas-x-tweets-possibly-200420690.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The next day he tweeted "that was my last time coming out the closet i promise".<ref>{{Cite twitter|number=1612938000874471426|user=lilnasx|title=that was my last time coming out the closet i promise|first=Montero|last=Hill|author-link=Lil Nas X|date=January 10, 2023|access-date=January 15, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230118095046/https://twitter.com/lilnasx/status/1612938000874471426|archive-date=January 18, 2023|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Shearing |first=Lois |date=January 11, 2023 |title=Did Lil Nas X just come out as bisexual? |url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/love-sex/a42459226/lil-nas-x-bisexual/ |access-date=February 12, 2023 |website=Cosmopolitan |language=en-GB |archive-date=February 12, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230212021218/https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/love-sex/a42459226/lil-nas-x-bisexual/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In November 2023, he tweeted that he was "still gay."<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1729717050120032316|user=lilnasx|title=not gonna lie i wanted to reinvent myself for this next era but sadly im still gay|first=Montero|last=Hill|author-link=Lil Nas X|date=November 28, 2023|access-date=January 10, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240110162632/http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:https://twitter.com/LilNasX/status/1729717050120032316&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&hl=en-us&client=safari|archive-date=January 10, 2024|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Religion===
Lil Nas X stated in September 2021 that he was an atheist "at one point," but is now "a very [[Spiritual but not religious|spiritual]] person in terms of the Universe, how everything works."<ref>{{Cite news |last=XXL Staff |date=September 28, 2021 |title=Lil Nas X Opens Up About His Battle for Respect in Hip-Hop |work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]] |url=https://www.xxlmag.com/lil-nas-x-interview/ |access-date=November 16, 2021 |archive-date=November 16, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211116061155/https://www.xxlmag.com/lil-nas-x-interview/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2023, he wrote that he was entering his "Christian era".<ref>Emily Brown, [https://relevantmagazine.com/culture/lil-nas-x-responds-to-accusations-that-hes-mocking-christianity/ Lil Nas X Responds to Accusations That He's "Mocking Christianity"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231222150848/https://relevantmagazine.com/culture/lil-nas-x-responds-to-accusations-that-hes-mocking-christianity/ |date=December 22, 2023 }}, relevantmagazine.com, USA, December 6, 2023</ref>

