==Accolades==
{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Lil Nas X}}

[[File:191125 Lil Nas X at the 2019 American Music Awards.png|thumb|upright|left|Lil Nas X at the [[American Music Awards of 2019|2019 American Music Awards]]]]
Lil Nas X is the recipient of multiple awards including two [[Grammy Award]]s, five [[Billboard Music Awards]], five [[MTV Video Music Awards]], two [[BET Hip Hop Awards]], two [[iHeartRadio Music Awards]] and two [[American Music Awards]]. He has also been awarded by [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]] as the youngest honoree of the [[Hal David Starlight Award]].

Lil Nas X was the most-nominated male artist at the [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards]],<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Warner |first=Denise |date=November 20, 2019 |title=2020 Grammy Nominees: The Complete List |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8544267/2020-grammy-nominations-complete-list |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=November 20, 2019 |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131144741/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8544267/2020-grammy-nominations-complete-list |url-status=live }}</ref> where he ultimately won awards for [[Best Music Video]] and [[Best Pop Duo/Group Performance]]. Lil Nas X is also the first openly LGBT Black artist to win a [[Country Music Association]] award<ref name="CMAboll">{{Cite web |last=Bollinger |first=Alex |date=November 14, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X is the first openly gay black artist to win a Country Music Award |url=https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2019/11/lil-nas-x-first-gay-person-win-country-music-award/ |access-date=November 15, 2019 |website=[[LGBTQ Nation]] |archive-date=November 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115153216/https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2019/11/lil-nas-x-first-gay-person-win-country-music-award/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and the first openly LGBTQ person to win an [[2019 MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Music Award]] for Song of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Yang |first=Nico |date=August 27, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X Is First LGBTQ+ Musician to Win 'Song of the Year' at VMAs |url=https://www.out.com/celebs/2019/8/27/lil-nas-x-first-lgbtq-musician-win-song-year-vmas |access-date=August 29, 2019 |website=Out |archive-date=August 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829093628/https://www.out.com/celebs/2019/8/27/lil-nas-x-first-lgbtq-musician-win-song-year-vmas |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2021, he became the third artist, following [[Kendrick Lamar]] and [[Taylor Swift]], to win an [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year]] for a video he co-directed – "[[Montero (Call Me by Your Name)]]".

Lil Nas X scored three number-one singles on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart. In early July 2019, "Old Town Road" achieved its 13th week at the top spot on the ''Billboard'' 100, becoming the [[List of Billboard Hot 100 chart achievements and milestones|first hip hop song to do so]].<ref name="Hot 100 record" />{{efn|It surpassed three hip hop songs that were tied at twelve weeks each: "[[Lose Yourself]]" by [[Eminem]] (2002), "[[Boom Boom Pow]]" by [[The Black Eyed Peas]] (2009), and "[[See You Again]]" by [[Wiz Khalifa]] featuring [[Charlie Puth]] (2015).<ref name="Hot 100 record">{{Cite magazine |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=July 1, 2019 |title=Lil Nas X's 'Old Town Road' Tops Hot 100 for a Hip-Hop Record 13th Week; Shawn Mendes & Camila Cabello's 'Senorita' Debuts at No. 2 |url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-number-one-hot-100-13-weeks/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=January 27, 2023 |archive-date=January 27, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230127131056/https://www.billboard.com/pro/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-number-one-hot-100-13-weeks/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On its fourteenth week at the top, it was the tenth single to ever reach the mark, with [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] noting all but two of the previous singles had been nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Grein |first=Paul |date=July 8, 2019 |title=With 14 Weeks Atop Hot 100, Will Lil Nas X's 'Old Town Road' Get Any Grammy Love? |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8518989/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-grammys-chances-14-weeks-hot-100 |magazine=Billboard |access-date=July 9, 2019 |archive-date=July 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710010115/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8518989/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-grammys-chances-14-weeks-hot-100 |url-status=live }}</ref>}} It is also the first song to sell 10 million copies while in the top spot.<ref name=":2" /><ref name="Hot 100 record" /> On its 15th week at the top, Lil Nas X became the first [[openly gay]] artist to have a song last as long, overtaking [[Elton John]]'s 1997 [[Double A-Side]]—where both sides of the [[Single (music)|record]] are promoted as hits, "[[Candle in the Wind 1997]]"/"[[Something About the Way You Look Tonight]]".<ref name="VultureHistory" /> At 19 weeks at number one, Lil Nas X holds the record for the most weeks since the chart was first introduced in 1958.<ref name="autogenerated2" />{{efn|Lil Nas X beat two songs tied at sixteen weeks for the longest time to do so; "[[One Sweet Day]]" by [[Mariah Carey]] and [[R&B]] group [[Boyz II Men]] (1995–1996); and "[[Despacito]]" by [[Luis Fonsi]] and [[Daddy Yankee]] featuring [[Justin Bieber]] (2017).}} {{As of|2019|August|df=}}, the song has also charted 19 weeks atop the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart;<ref name="autogenerated2" /> beating a three-way tie record.<ref>{{Cite web |last=McIntyre |first=Hugh |date=August 1, 2019 |title='Old Town Road' Is One Week Away From Beating One Of Drake's Most Important Chart Records |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2019/08/01/old-town-road-is-one-week-away-from-beating-one-of-drakes-most-important-chart-records/ |access-date=August 3, 2019 |website=[[Forbes]] |language=en |archive-date=August 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802163903/https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2019/08/01/old-town-road-is-one-week-away-from-beating-one-of-drakes-most-important-chart-records/ |url-status=live }}</ref>{{efn|On the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart: at nineteen weeks it beats the three songs at eighteen weeks:
* "[[The Honeydripper]] (Parts 1 & 2)" (1945) by [[Joe Liggins]] and His Honeydrippers,<ref name="whitburnr&b">{{Cite book |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |url=https://archive.org/details/joelwhitburnstopr00whit |title=Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singlessongs: 1942–2004 |publisher=Record Research |year=2004 |isbn=0-89820-115-2 |author-link=Joel Whitburn |url-access=registration}}</ref>
* "[[Choo Choo Ch'Boogie]]" (1946) by [[Louis Jordan and His Tympany Five]],<ref name="whitburnr&b" /> and
* "[[One Dance]]" (2016) by [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] featuring [[Wizkid]] and [[Kyla (British singer)|Kyla]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=September 8, 2016 |title=Summer '16: Drake's 'One Dance' Set Record for Most Weeks Atop Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs, Won Song of the Summer Honors & More |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7502853/summer-16-drake-one-dance-record-most-weeks-atop-hot-r-and-b-hip-hop-chart |magazine=Billboard |access-date=April 22, 2018 |archive-date=May 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524203332/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7502853/summer-16-drake-one-dance-record-most-weeks-atop-hot-r-and-b-hip-hop-chart |url-status=live }}</ref>}} At 19 weeks at the top of the [[Hot Rap Songs]] chart the song has also beaten a three-way tie.<ref name="autogenerated2" />{{efn|Three songs were tied at 18 weeks each: "[[Hot Boyz (song)|Hot Boyz]]" by [[Missy "Misdemeanor" Elliott]] featuring [[Lil' Mo]], [[Nas]], [[Eve (rapper)|Eve]] and [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]] (1999–2000); "[[Fancy (Iggy Azalea song)|Fancy]]" by [[Iggy Azalea]] featuring [[Charli XCX]] (2014); and "[[Hotline Bling]]" by [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] (2015–2016).<ref name="HotlineBling">{{Cite magazine |last=Mendizabal |first=Amaya |date=January 25, 2016 |title=Drake's 'Hotline Bling' Ties Hot Rap Songs Chart Record |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6851831/drake-hotline-bling-ties-hot-rap-songs-chart-record |magazine=Billboard |access-date=May 15, 2018 |archive-date=May 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523065922/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6851831/drake-hotline-bling-ties-hot-rap-songs-chart-record |url-status=live }}</ref>}} By November 2019, the song was [[Diamond Certified]], moving a combined sales and streaming 10 million units.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=Walker |first=Yvette |date=October 28, 2019 |title=Country or Hip Hop? |url=https://medium.com/@ywalker/country-or-hip-hop-f2ac85a6f455 |access-date=November 16, 2019 |website=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] |language=en |archive-date=November 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116142516/https://medium.com/@ywalker/country-or-hip-hop-f2ac85a6f455 |url-status=live }}</ref>

''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' named him as one of the 25 most influential people on the Internet in 2019, for his "global impact on social media" and "overall ability to drive news".<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The 25 Most Influential People on the Internet |url=https://time.com/5626827/the-25-most-influential-people-on-the-internet/ |magazine=Time |language=en-us |access-date=June 8, 2020 |archive-date=July 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717004728/https://time.com/5626827/the-25-most-influential-people-on-the-internet/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2020, he was named on the ''[[Forbes]]'' [[30 Under 30]] list.<ref name="auto"/> In 2021, he appeared on the [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s annual list of the 100 most influential people in the world.<ref name="Sachdeva"/> On September 1, 2021, The Trevor Project announced that Lil Nas X is the recipient of its inaugural Suicide Prevention Advocate of the Year award.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=September 2021 |title=Lil Nas X to be Honored as The Trevor Project's Suicide Prevention Advocate of the Year |url=https://www.billboard.com/video/lil-nas-x-to-be-honored-as-the-trevor-projects-suicide-prevention-advocate-of-the-year-billboard-news |magazine=Billboard |access-date=September 6, 2021 |archive-date=September 5, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210905102457/https://www.billboard.com/video/lil-nas-x-to-be-honored-as-the-trevor-projects-suicide-prevention-advocate-of-the-year-billboard-news |url-status=live }}</ref>

